INSERT INTO `documentations` (`id`, `name`, `description`, `desc_short`, `keywords`, `content`, `duration`, `type`, `category_id`, `target_collection`, `sort_order`, `is_active`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `regenerate_audios`, `active_map_run_id`) VALUES ('542', 'mod_kaggle', NULL, NULL, NULL, '# SAGE Module: Kaggle Notebooks (`kaggle.php`)

---

## 1. Introduction Paragraph

The Kaggle Notebooks module is SAGE''s remote compute orchestration layer, enabling users to manage, sync, and launch Jupyter notebooks on Kaggle''s cloud GPU infrastructure directly from the SAGE dashboard. It solves the problem of needing free, high-powered GPU execution (Stable Diffusion, AI training tasks) without local hardware, by treating Kaggle as a remote execution backend that can be triggered, monitored, and kept in sync from within SAGE. The module bridges a PHP/MariaDB frontend with a Python FastAPI service (`kaggle_service.py`) that wraps the Kaggle CLI via subprocess, and it uses the Zrok reverse-proxy token system to securely pass credentials to running notebooks. In the overall SAGE pipeline it sits at the infrastructure tier — separate from the narrative or image-generation modules — and acts as the compute dispatch mechanism for any notebook-based workloads.

---

## 2. Module Details

### Purpose & Scope

The Kaggle module manages the full lifecycle of Kaggle Jupyter notebooks from within SAGE:

- **Credential management** — stores Kaggle API credentials (`kaggle.json`) and a Zrok reverse-proxy token in the project''s `token/` directory.
- **Notebook inventory** — enumerates both local notebooks (`.ipynb` files under `notebooks/kaggle/`) and the authenticated user''s remote Kaggle kernels, presenting them in a unified table.
- **Sync & Run** — pulls the latest remote version of a notebook, auto-fixes kernel metadata (GPU on, internet on, Zrok dataset attached), then pushes it back to Kaggle to trigger execution.
- **Zrok dataset sync** — packages the Zrok token into a private Kaggle dataset (`sage-zrok-token`) so running notebooks can retrieve it programmatically without hardcoding secrets.

**Pipeline position:** Infrastructure / remote compute dispatch. Not directly tied to narrative or image generation logic; it is the execution substrate that those pipelines can target.

---

### Key Features

| Feature | Description |
|---|---|
| **Unified notebook table** | Merges local `.ipynb` files with remote Kaggle kernels by slug-matching. Shows sync status: *Synced*, *Remote only*, or *Local only*. |
| **Sync & Run** | One-click: pull remote → fix metadata → push back (triggers "Save Version & Run All" on Kaggle). |
| **Push (local)** | Pushes the local folder directly without pulling first. Auto-creates `kernel-metadata.json` if absent. |
| **Pull** | Downloads a remote kernel to `notebooks/kaggle/<slug>/`. |
| **Status check** | AJAX endpoint (`?ajax=status&kernel_ref=…`) polls kernel run state (running / queued / complete). |
| **Auto metadata fix** | `fixKernelMetadata()` ensures `enable_gpu=true`, `enable_internet=true`, Zrok dataset in `dataset_sources`, and a valid `id` field. |
| **Default metadata creation** | `createDefaultMetadata()` scaffolds a `kernel-metadata.json` from the first `.ipynb` found, using the Kaggle username from the stored token. |
| **Zrok dataset sync** | `syncZrokTokenDataset()` — upsert logic: attempts `datasets version` first, falls back to `datasets create` if 404. |
| **Credential forms** | Independent save paths for Kaggle API key and Zrok token. Saving both together auto-triggers Zrok dataset sync. |
| **Collapsible sections** | Three sections (API Configuration, Notebooks, zrok) collapse/expand with `localStorage` persistence. |
| **Embedded zrok iframe** | Scaled 50% iframe of `https://api.zrok.io/` embedded in the zrok card for quick token inspection. |

---

### Data Model

This module does **not** read from or write to any SAGE MariaDB tables. All persistence is file-based:

| File | Location | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `kaggle.json` | `token/.kaggle/kaggle.json` | Kaggle API credentials (`username`, `key`). chmod 600. |
| `.zrok_api_key` | `token/.zrok_api_key` | Zrok reverse-proxy token. chmod 600. |
| `kernel-metadata.json` | `notebooks/kaggle/<slug>/` | Kaggle kernel manifest per notebook. |
| `dataset-metadata.json` | `<tmpdir>/` (ephemeral) | Used during Zrok dataset sync; created in `/tmp`, cleaned up after. |
| `.ipynb` files | `notebooks/kaggle/<slug>/` | Notebook source files; scanned by `listLocalNotebooks()`. |

Downloaded datasets are stored under `pyapi/datasets/`, pulled kernels under `pyapi/kernels/`, and model files under `pyapi/models/` (managed by the PyAPI layer).

---

### API / Backend Integration

All Kaggle operations flow through the **SAGE PyAPI** (`pyapi/main.py`) on `http://127.0.0.1:8009`. The Kaggle service is registered dynamically via the `ServiceRegistry` and mounted under the `/kaggle` prefix.

#### PyAPI Endpoints (all `POST` unless noted)

| Endpoint | Method | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `/kaggle/competitions/list` | POST | List competitions with search/sort/page. |
| `/kaggle/competitions/download` | POST | Download competition data to `pyapi/datasets/competitions/`. |
| `/kaggle/competitions/submit` | POST | Submit a file to a competition. |
| `/kaggle/datasets/list` | POST | Search/list public or user datasets. |
| `/kaggle/datasets/files` | POST | List files within a dataset. |
| `/kaggle/datasets/download` | POST | Download a dataset (with optional unzip). |
| `/kaggle/datasets/create` | POST | Create a new Kaggle dataset from a local path (`--dir-mode zip`). |
| `/kaggle/datasets/version` | POST | Create a new dataset version; falls back to `create` on 404. |
| `/kaggle/datasets/delete` | POST | Delete a dataset by ref; treats 404 as success. |
| `/kaggle/kernels/list` | POST | List kernels (returns CSV + parsed JSON). Supports `--mine`, `--user`, `--page-size`. |
| `/kaggle/kernels/push` | POST | Push a local kernel folder to Kaggle. |
| `/kaggle/kernels/pull` | POST | Pull a remote kernel to a local path. |
| `/kaggle/kernels/output` | POST | Download kernel output files. |
| `/kaggle/kernels/status` | POST | Get run status of a kernel. |
| `/kaggle/config/view` | GET | Show current Kaggle CLI config. |
| `/kaggle/config/set` | POST | Set a Kaggle CLI config value. |
| `/kaggle/status` | GET | Health check — verifies CLI version and returns endpoint map. |

The PHP layer (`KaggleAPI.php`) communicates with these endpoints via cURL. `KaggleService.php` wraps `KaggleAPI` with higher-level operations (pull+fix+push, merge local/remote, etc.).

The PyAPI itself calls the **Kaggle CLI** via `subprocess.run()` using argument-list style (no shell injection risk). `KAGGLE_CONFIG_DIR` is injected into the subprocess environment from `main.py`''s startup configuration.

No external AI provider calls (Pollinations, Groq, etc.) are made by this module. No scheduler job triggers.

---

### UI & Interaction

**Layout (mobile-first, single-column):**

1. **Header bar** — gradient using `--accent` CSS variable; title and subtitle.
2. **Message area** — per-action flash messages (success / error / warning) rendered above cards.
3. **API Configuration card** — collapsible. Shows binary path and config directory. Form fields: Kaggle Username, Kaggle API Key, Zrok Token (both password inputs pre-filled from stored values). Single "Save Credentials" button. If both tokens are absent, a warning box disables the notebooks section visually.
4. **Notebooks card** — collapsible. Gated behind `$hasRequiredTokens`. Shows a unified table of all known notebooks with columns: Notebook (title + ref), Sync Status badge, Actions.
   - **Actions per row** vary by state: remote-only shows Sync & Run + Status + Pull; synced shows Sync & Run + Status + Push; local-only shows Push.
   - confirm() dialogs on destructive/long actions.
5. **zrok card** — collapsible. Contains a scaled (50%) iframe of `https://api.zrok.io/` with a Reload button. Only shown when `$hasRequiredTokens` is true.

**AJAX:** `checkStatus()` in JS hits `?ajax=status&kernel_ref=…` and injects a status badge into the row''s status div without a page reload.

**Theme:** Uses Forge UI CSS variable system (`--accent`, `--card`, `--text`, `--text-muted`, etc.) via `base.css`. Dark/light theme switching is inherited from the global `data-theme` / `localStorage(''spw_theme'')` mechanism — no module-level override needed.

**Mobile:** Buttons stack vertically below 768px. Card padding reduces. Table font size reduces to 13px. All buttons go full-width.

**Collapse persistence:** Section open/closed state is saved to `localStorage` keyed as `kaggle-<section>-collapsed`.

---

### Dependencies & Related Modules

| Dependency | Type | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `pyapi/main.py` | Runtime | ServiceRegistry loads `kaggle_service.py`; PyAPI must be running on port 8009. |
| `pyapi/services/kaggle_service.py` | Runtime | FastAPI router; wraps Kaggle CLI via subprocess. |
| `src/Kaggle/KaggleAPI.php` | PHP class | Low-level cURL client for the PyAPI. |
| `src/Kaggle/KaggleService.php` | PHP class | Business logic layer; used directly by `kaggle.php`. |
| `public/bootstrap.php` | Runtime | SAGE core bootstrap (DB, session, etc.). |
| `public/env_locals.php` | Runtime | Local environment overrides. |
| `App\Core\SpwBase` | Runtime | Provides `renderLayout()` and `getProjectPath()`. |
| `/css/base.css` | Frontend | Forge UI design tokens and base styles. |
| Kaggle CLI (`kaggle`) | Runtime | Must be installed and accessible; path discovered via `which kaggle` or hardcoded candidates. |
| Zrok | External service | `https://api.zrok.io/` — reverse proxy for tunnelling into running Kaggle notebooks. |

This module is accessed from the SAGE dashboard navigation. It does not directly link into other production pipeline modules (narrative, image gen, etc.) but provides the compute layer they may dispatch to.

---

### Known State / Notes

- **Competitions and datasets endpoints** are implemented in the PyAPI and PHP client but the `kaggle.php` UI only exposes the notebook (kernel) workflow. Competition/dataset operations are available via the API but have no dedicated UI panel in the current view.
- **`listKernels` page_size parameter:** The `KernelListRequest` Pydantic model accepts `page_size` (maps to `--page-size`), but the PHP `KaggleService::listRemoteKernels()` currently hardcodes `$page_size = 100` without passing it to `KaggleAPI::listKernels()`. The `listKernels()` PHP method signature does not yet expose `page_size` as a parameter. `[VERIFY]`
- **CSV parsing fallback:** The PyAPI cleans Kaggle''s stdout of leading `Warning:` lines and attempts to parse the result as CSV into a `parsed` JSON array. The PHP layer prefers `parsed` if present but falls back to manual CSV parsing. This two-layer approach was added to handle Kaggle CLI permission warnings on Termux.
- **`versionDataset` upsert logic:** The PHP `syncZrokTokenDataset()` calls `versionDataset()` first, then falls back to `createDataset()` on failure. The PyAPI `datasets/version` endpoint mirrors this: it attempts `kaggle datasets version`, then falls back to `kaggle datasets create` on 404/not-found stderr. This means two levels of upsert fallback exist — one in PHP, one in Python.
- **`deleteDataset`** — implemented in both PyAPI and PHP client but not exposed in the UI. `[VERIFY - confirm no UI trigger exists]`
- **Zrok iframe** — the embedded iframe at `https://api.zrok.io/` may be blocked by the site''s `X-Frame-Options` or CSP headers in some browser configurations. The Reload button re-sets `iframe.src` to force a refresh.
- **`pushAndRunRemoteKernel()`** — implemented in `KaggleService` (pull to tmp → push back) but not used in the current `kaggle.php` UI; `sync_and_run` action instead calls `pullKernelToLocal()` + `fixKernelMetadata()` + `pushAndRunKernelFolder()` in sequence. `[VERIFY - confirm pushAndRunRemoteKernel is dead code in UI]`
- **Termux compatibility:** The PyAPI uses zero pip dependencies beyond `fastapi`, `pydantic`, and the standard library for this service. Subprocess-based CLI wrapping was chosen explicitly to avoid Conda/venv conflicts in the Termux environment.
- **`set_time_limit`** — PHP POST handlers for `sync_and_run`, `pull_notebook`, and `run_local` call `set_time_limit(120–180)` to allow for slow Kaggle CLI network operations.
', '0', 'md', '1', NULL, '0', '1', '2026-05-31 05:12:41', '2026-05-31 05:12:41', '0', NULL);
INSERT INTO `documentations` (`id`, `name`, `description`, `desc_short`, `keywords`, `content`, `duration`, `type`, `category_id`, `target_collection`, `sort_order`, `is_active`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `regenerate_audios`, `active_map_run_id`) VALUES ('541', 'mod_entity_gallery_system', NULL, NULL, NULL, '# SAGE Module: Entity Gallery System
`sage_module_entity_gallery_system.md`

---

## Relationship to Enhanimaticism

> **See also:** `sage_module_enhanimaticism.md`

Before reading this document, it is worth noting that SAGE has a separate, more modern module — **Enhanimaticism** (`enhanimaticism.php`) — which handles any frame-based entity type through a single unified PHP interface. Enhanimaticism is the most advanced and most fully developed approach to entity and frame management in the platform: it covers browsing, reviewing, batch processing, editing, filtering, CRUD operations, and much more, all within one cohesive and highly usable interface. It is also the most actively developed of the two approaches.

The per-entity views documented here are older and leaner by design. They remain in the platform because each offers a distinct interaction style that Enhanimaticism does not replicate:

- The **CRUD view** provides a text-focused, table-driven record management interface — well suited for direct prompt editing and bulk data work
- The **gallery view** delivers a purely image-grid-centred browsing experience with minimal surrounding UI
- The **map runs view** offers a unique horizontal frame-chain layout for reviewing batch generation runs in chronological sequence

These views have their own vibe and serve specific focused workflows. They coexist with Enhanimaticism rather than being replaced by it.

---

## 1. Introduction Paragraph

The Entity Gallery System is SAGE''s standard production interface pattern applied consistently across every visual and narrative entity in *The Anima Chronicles* pipeline. Each entity type — characters, locations, sketches, generatives, and more — owns its own dedicated set of files: a PHP CRUD manager, a gallery class extending `AbstractNuGallery`, a gallery entry point, a Map Runs view, and its own database table plus associated views. These files follow a strong shared convention (Forge UI design system, common column patterns, the same three-view structure) but are individually authored and maintained, not auto-generated from a single generic registration. Among all entity types, **Sketches** is the most developed, carrying exclusive subsystems — including narrative curation scoring (`sketch_analysis`) and sequence analysis (`sketch_sequence_analysis`) — that have no equivalent elsewhere in the platform.

---

## 2. Module Details

### Purpose & Scope

The Entity Gallery System is not a single module or framework — it is a **convention** that every visual entity in SAGE implements independently. Each entity type owns its own full file set:

| File | Per-entity example |
|---|---|
| `sql_crud_{entity}.php` | `sql_crud_sketches.php` |
| `gallery_{entity}_nu.php` | `gallery_sketches_nu.php` |
| `src/Gallery/{Entity}NuGallery.php` | `src/Gallery/SketchesNuGallery.php` |
| `view_map_runs_{entity}.php` | `view_map_runs_sketches.php` |
| `{entity}` DB table | `sketches` |
| `v_gallery_{entity}` DB view | `v_gallery_sketches` |

These files are individually authored. They share a strong structural convention — the same base class (`AbstractNuGallery`), the same Forge UI design system, the same column naming patterns, the same three-view purpose — but each entity''s files exist as concrete, maintained code. Adding a new entity type to SAGE means writing all of these files from scratch, following the established pattern. The shared infrastructure (`AbstractNuGallery`, `GearMenuModule`, `ImageEditorModule`, `ModuleRegistry`, `forge_tool.php`, `modal_frame_details.php`) reduces the per-entity authoring burden significantly, but the entity files themselves are not generated or registered automatically.

The system collectively handles:

- **Record management** — create, read, update, delete, copy, reorder entity records
- **Visual browsing** — paginated, filterable gallery of generated frames per entity
- **Batch run review** — chronological inspection of AI image generation runs grouped by `map_runs` batch

It sits at the intersection of the **data management layer** (MariaDB per-entity tables and views), the **image generation pipeline** (scheduler, `frames`, `map_runs`), and the **review/curation workflow** (gear menu, image editor, frame details modal).

---

### Entity Roster

The following entity types each have a full CRUD + Gallery + Map Runs view set. Entity types are divided into three categories by capability.

#### Visual Entities (frames, galleries, map runs)

| Entity | Icon | Scheduler ID | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `characters` | 🦸 | 11 | |
| `factions` | 🎌 | — | |
| `character_poses` | 🤸 | 19 | |
| `character_anima_poses` | 🤹 | — | |
| `character_expressions` | 🧑‍🎤 | — | |
| `animas` | 🐾 | 12 | |
| `locations` | 🗺️ | 13 | |
| `backgrounds` | 🏞️ | 16 | |
| `artifacts` | 🏺 | 18 | |
| `vehicles` | 🛸 | 17 | |
| `scene_parts` | 🎬 | — | |
| `controlnet_maps` | ☠️ | 20 | |
| `spawns` | 🌱 | — | |
| `generatives` | ⚡ | 10 | |
| `sketches` | 🪄 | 15 | Most developed — see Sketches-Exclusive Subsystems below |
| `prompt_matrix_blueprints` | 🌌 | 23 | |
| `composites` | 🧩 | 24 | Extra: Multiplane/MultiVid modal (🧩 button) |

#### Video Entities

| Entity | Icon | Scheduler ID | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `animatics` | 🎥 | — | Frames contain video rather than images |

#### System Entities (no frames or galleries)

| Entity | Icon | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `pastebin` | 📋 | Text/clipboard storage |
| `sage_todos` | 🎫 | Internal task tracking |
| `meta_entities` | 📦 | Generic metadata records |

---

### The Three-View Triad

Each visual entity type has its own concrete implementation of these three views. The files look very similar across entities — they share the same structure, the same AJAX action names, the same Forge UI styling — but each is its own authored PHP file with entity-specific column handling, filter logic, and any entity-level extensions.

#### 1. CRUD View — `sql_crud_{entity}.php`

The data management interface. Each entity has its own file; all follow the same internal structure.

**Core capabilities (all entities):**
- Schema auto-discovery via `SHOW COLUMNS` — optional features (ordering, regeneration flag, img2img, ControlNet map, active map run selector) activate automatically when the corresponding columns exist
- Paginated record table rendered inside a Swiper carousel; pages load via AJAX on slide change
- Inline `contenteditable` editing for `name`, `description`, `prompt_negative`
- Add / Copy / Delete / Drag-to-reorder
- Bulk ASC/DESC sort via `/order_recalc.php`
- Regeneration checkbox (`regenerate_images = 1`) to queue records for the next scheduler pass
- Per-row active map run selector
- Scheduler trigger button (🌀) when a scheduler ID is registered
- Prompt Matrix link (✺) → `view_prompt_matrix.php?entity_type={entity}&entity_id=…`
- Frame Details modal (🕸️) → `window.showEntityFormInModal(entity, id)`
- Thumbnail gallery for img2img and ControlNet map frame references (PhotoSwipe lightbox; double-click to remove)
- Mobile card-collapse layout below 768 px

**Entity-specific overrides:**
- `composites` — adds a 🧩 Multiplane button calling `window.showMultiplaneInModal(id)`
- `sketches` — entity icon links to `view_map_runs_sketches.php` rather than the standard gallery

#### 2. Gallery View — `gallery_{entity}_nu.php` + `src/Gallery/{Entity}NuGallery.php`

The visual frame browser. Each entity has its own entry point PHP file and its own gallery class extending `AbstractNuGallery`. The base class provides the Swiper pagination, PhotoSwipe lightbox, AJAX loading, filter rendering, and gear/image-editor integration. Each entity''s gallery class implements the entity-specific contract.

**Core capabilities (all entities):**
- Swiper-based pagination with lazy AJAX page loading
- PhotoSwipe lightbox with optional gear menu (⚙️) and frame details (🎯) buttons
- Grid / Pic toggle (masonry vs single-image view, no page reload)
- Filter bar — entity-specific `<select>` dropdowns; form submits on change
- GearMenu module with standard entity actions (injected via `ModuleRegistry`)
- ImageEditor module — mask, crop, transform, filter tabs
- Full-text caption modal (📖)
- `forge_tool.php` floatool

**Each `{Entity}NuGallery` class implements:**
- `getFiltersFromRequest()` — which GET params constitute filters
- `getFilterOptions()` — what values populate the filter dropdowns
- `getWhereClause()` — SQL WHERE applied to the gallery view
- `getCaptionFields()` — which fields appear in the caption below each image
- `getBaseQuery()` — the `v_gallery_{entity}` database view to query
- `getToggleButtonLeft()` — pixel offset for the grid/pic toggle button

#### 3. Map Runs View — `view_map_runs_{entity}.php`

The batch generation explorer. Each entity has its own file. All follow the same structure — paginated run listing, per-run frame chain Swiper, note editing, regenerate trigger — but each file is concrete and entity-specific in its queries, ingredient display, and any extended metadata.

**Core capabilities (all entities):**
- Paginated run listing (`map_runs WHERE entity_type = ''{entity}''`)
- Search across run ID, note text, and frame prompts/names
- Per-run frame chain rendered as a horizontal Swiper carousel (`slidesPerView: ''auto''`, free-mode)
- Chain cards: thumbnail, frame ID, entity badge, generation method badge (Original / Img2Img / Edit)
- Inline run note editing with save indicator
- Regenerate run button — sets `regenerate_images = 1` on all sketch/entity records in the run
- Link to `view_scrollmagic_map_run.php` per run
- GearMenu + ImageEditor modules
- PhotoSwipe lightbox across all run frames

---

### Sketches-Exclusive Subsystems

While all entity types share the triad above, **Sketches** has additional subsystems with no equivalent elsewhere in the platform:

#### `sketch_ingredients`
Flexible prompt ingredient system. Each sketch record can have multiple typed ingredient rows (`ingredient_type`, `source_id`, `prompt_fragment`, `snapshot_data`) sourced from characters, locations, templates, interactions, styles, generator configs, and Anivoc vocabulary. Displayed as an "Ingredients (n)" pill in the Map Runs view, opening a detail modal.

#### `sketch_analysis`
AI-generated curation scoring per sketch. Stores `overall_quality` (numeric score), `classification` (narrative function, emotional tone — JSON), `scoring` (4-axis breakdown: narrative completeness, visual impact, production readiness, visual distinctiveness — JSON), `entities` (characters, artifacts present — JSON), `thematics` (primary themes — JSON), and `recommendations` (potential use — JSON). Surfaced as a "🕵️ Analysis (score)" pill in the Map Runs view.

#### `sketch_sequence_analysis`
Sequence-level narrative analysis across groups of sketch frames. `[VERIFY: view/API integration details — not present in current dump]`

#### `meta_sketches` (legacy)
Legacy metadata linking sketches to `generator_config`, `sketch_templates`, and `interactions`. Superseded by `sketch_ingredients` but still supported in the Map Runs view via a normalised fallback path.

#### `sketch_templates`
Named composition templates with `core_idea`, `shot_type`, `camera_angle`, and `perspective` fields. Used during prompt generation; surfaced in ingredient display.

---

### Shared Data Model

#### Universal Tables

| Table | Role |
|---|---|
| `frames` | All generated images across all entity types; `entity_type` + `entity_id` FK pattern |
| `map_runs` | Batch generation records; `entity_type` scopes runs to a specific entity |

#### Per-Entity Tables

Each visual entity has its own table (e.g. `characters`, `locations`, `sketches`) following a common column pattern:

