---

## Introduction

The Motion Editor is SAGE''s real-time 3D scene compositor and camera direction tool, built on top of Three.js and tied directly to the animatic pipeline. It takes an animatic record as its context and assembles a live WebGL stage from all linked assets — background images rendered on a scrolling cylinder, plane-mapped videos and sprites, and GLTF/GLB 3D models — allowing the producer to precisely position, scale, rotate, and animate every layer before recording the result as a video take. The editor stores full telemetry data alongside each recording, enabling non-destructive replay of any prior take. Its `lil-gui` control panel is draggable, persistent across sessions via `localStorage`, and fully usable on the Android/Chrome mobile environment that SAGE runs on.

---

## Purpose & Scope

The Motion Editor bridges the static image/video asset library and the finished animatic output. Its job is to take assets that have been associated with a specific animatic (frames, videos, meshes) and allow the producer to:

- Arrange those assets in a live 3D scene with precise spatial control
- Set camera position, FOV, orbit constraints, and damping
- Apply physics-like effects to actors (sway, vibration, emissive glow)
- Record the resulting scene as a WebM/MP4 video
- Store telemetry data (per-frame positions of all layers plus camera state) for replay and review

It occupies a full-viewport page in the pipeline, accessed with a required `animatic_id` query parameter. Its output (recorded videos) feeds back into the `videos` and `videos_2_animatics` tables, making recorded takes available as regular video assets in the rest of SAGE.

---

## Key Features

### Layer System

Each asset linked to the animatic is loaded as a layer object in the Three.js scene. Layers have three roles:

- `background` — rendered on the interior of a scrolling cylinder (radius 40, length 160), simulating a parallax sky/environment scroll. Uses `THREE.CylinderGeometry` with `DoubleSide` material.
- `plane` — a `THREE.PlaneGeometry` carrying either a static image texture or a `THREE.VideoTexture`. Oriented flat on the stage by default.
- `model3d` — a GLTF/GLB mesh loaded via `GLTFLoader`, auto-scaled and centred, with configurable scale factor, emissive intensity, and full XYZ rotation.

On first load, the backend auto-syncs all assets linked to the animatic into the `motion_layers` table if they are not already present, assigning default z-indices and role-appropriate `layer_config` JSON.

### Camera System

Camera is a `THREE.PerspectiveCamera` controlled by `OrbitControls`. All parameters are exposed in the GUI:

| Parameter | Range | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Position X/Y/Z | −100 to 100 / 0 to 200 / −100 to 100 | Manual sliders with `.listen()` for live feedback |
| FOV (Zoom) | 10–120 | Labelled "Zoom" in GUI |
| Polar constraints | 0 – π | Min/max polar angle |
| Azimuth constraints | −0.78 – 0.78 | Values >10 / <−10 treated as Infinity |
| Distance constraints | 10–100 / 50–500 | Min/max orbit distance |
| Damping factor | 0.05 default | Always enabled |
| Auto-spin | boolean | `autoRotate` + speed |
| Enable Pan / Rotate / Zoom | boolean | Each independently toggleable |

Camera state (position + `controls.target`) is captured into `CAM_PARAMS` on save and restored on next load from `motion_setups.environment_config`.

### Camera Presets

Camera configurations can be saved to and loaded from the `motion_camera_presets` table (auto-created at runtime if absent). Preset operations:

- **Load Preset** — populates a dropdown from the DB; selecting and clicking "Load Preset" applies all `CAM_PARAMS` from the stored JSON.
- **Save New** — prompts for a name; POSTs current `CAM_PARAMS` as JSON.
- **Update Current** — overwrites the currently-loaded preset with current camera state.

### Actor Transform Controls

The active layer is selected from a dropdown in the GUI. Once selected, the following are exposed:

- Position X / Y / Z
- Scale (uniform, applied relative to the mesh''s `userData.baseScale`)
- Z-Order (sort) — integer, maps to `mesh.renderOrder`
- Parallax (Depth Offset) — float, adjusts Y positioning formula
- Rotation: Pitch (X), Yaw (Y), Roll (Z) in radians
- Role toggle — reassigns the layer''s rendering mode and rebuilds the mesh object

### Drag & Drop Mode

When "🖐 Drag & Drop Mode" is enabled in the GUI, pointer-down events on the active layer''s mesh initiate a drag operation on a camera-facing plane. `OrbitControls` are disabled during the drag and re-enabled on pointer-up. Position is written back into both `ACTOR_PARAMS` and `l.config` in real time.

### Physics / Material

Per-actor, animatable properties applied in the render loop:

| Property | Behaviour |
|---|---|
| Sway Amplitude | Sinusoidal X-axis displacement |
| Sway Speed | Frequency multiplier for sway |
| Vibration | High-frequency Z-axis jitter (60 Hz) |
| Self-Glow (Emissive) | Sets `emissiveIntensity` on all child meshes of a `model3d` layer |

### Post-Processing

Uses `EffectComposer` with `AfterimagePass` (motion blur / trails). The `damp` uniform is exposed as "Blur Strength" in the Environment panel, range 0–0.99.

### Recording

Two recording modes selectable via GUI:

- **Video + Data** — captures the `renderer.domElement` canvas stream at 30 fps via `MediaRecorder`, prefers `video/webm;codecs=vp9`, falls back to `mp4`. Telemetry is also captured.
- **Data Only** — records telemetry only; no canvas capture. Indicator shown in blue.

On stop, a `FormData` POST is sent to `motion_api.php?action=save_video` with the video blob and/or telemetry JSON. The backend writes the video file, generates a placeholder JPEG thumbnail, inserts a `videos` record, and creates a `videos_2_animatics` link. A take record is always written to `motion_takes` with full telemetry JSON and duration.

A red REC indicator with a blinking dot and elapsed timer is shown during recording.

### Take Replay

A dropdown in the System panel lists all takes for the current animatic (from `motion_takes`). Selecting a take and pressing "► Play Take" fetches `telemetry_data` and replays it frame-by-frame using `Date.now()` elapsed time matching. Camera distance is replayed; layer positions and rotations are restored per frame. "■ Stop Replay" returns camera to saved position.

### Scenario Save

"💾 Save Scenario" serialises the full environment state — `ENV_PARAMS`, `CAM_PARAMS` (including `controls.target`), `TEX_PARAMS` — into `motion_setups.environment_config` as JSON, and updates all `motion_layers.layer_config` records with current per-layer transform/physics values.

### GUI Persistence

The draggable `lil-gui` panel saves its position and folder open/close states to `localStorage` under keys `sage_motion_gui_pos` and `sage_motion_gui_folders`. State is restored on next load and saved on page unload via `beforeunload`.

---

## Data Model

### Tables Read

| Table | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `motion_setups` | Load/create the active setup for the animatic; read `environment_config` |
| `motion_layers` | Load all layers for a setup; read `layer_config`, `role`, `z_index` |
| `animatic_frames` | Enumerate frame assets linked to this animatic |
| `animatic_videos` | Enumerate video assets linked to this animatic |
| `animatic_meshes` | Enumerate mesh assets linked to this animatic |
| `frames` | Resolve `frame_filename` for image layers |
| `videos` | Resolve `video_url` for video layers |
| `meshes` | Resolve `mesh_filename` for 3D model layers |
| `motion_camera_presets` | Load saved camera configurations |
| `motion_takes` | List available takes for replay |

### Tables Written

| Table | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `motion_setups` | Create default setup on first load; update `environment_config` on save |
| `motion_layers` | Insert auto-synced layers on first load; update `layer_config` and `role` on save |
| `motion_camera_presets` | Insert new presets; update existing presets |
| `motion_takes` | Insert telemetry record on each recording stop |
| `videos` | Insert new video record from recording |
| `videos_2_animatics` | Link newly recorded video to current animatic |
| `video_counter` | Increment counter for deterministic video filename generation |
| `map_runs` | Create a `map_run` record for each recorded video (via `FramesManager::createMapRun`) |
| `motion_camera_presets` | Auto-created at runtime if absent |

### Key JSON Structures

**`motion_setups.environment_config`** (top-level object):
```json
{
  "params": { "scrollSpeed": 4.0, "blurStrength": 0.9, "bgBrightness": 1.0, "bgTint": "#ffffff", "ambientInt": 2.0, "dirInt": 2.0, "fogNear": 200, "fogFar": 500, "fogColor": "#000000" },
  "camParams": { "camX": 0, "camY": 45, "camZ": 15, "targetX": 0, "targetY": 0, "targetZ": 0, "zoom": 60, ... },
  "texParams": { "repeatX": 4, "repeatY": 2, "offsetX": 0.5, "offsetY": 0.0 }
}
```

**`motion_layers.layer_config`** (per-layer object, keys vary by role):
```json
{
  "posX": 0, "posY": 45, "posZ": 0,
  "scaleFactor": 1.0,
  "rotX": -1.57, "rotY": 0.0, "rotZ": 0.0,
  "zIndex": 3,
  "depthOffset": 0.0,
  "swayAmp": 0, "swaySpeed": 1, "vibration": 0.0, "emissiveInt": 0.0
}
```

**`motion_takes.telemetry_data`** (array of frame snapshots):
```json
[
  {
    "time": 0.033,
    "cam": { "r": 0.0, "p": 1.1, "d": 55.0 },
    "layers": { "12": { "x": 0, "y": 45, "z": 0, "rx": -1.57, "ry": 0, "rz": 0 } }
  }
]
```

---

## API / Backend Integration

All backend communication is handled by `motion_api.php`.

| Action | Method | Key Parameters | Response |
|---|---|---|---|
| `load_setup` | GET | `animatic_id` | Setup row + full layers array with resolved filenames |
| `save_setup` | POST | `setup_id`, `environment_config`, `layers_config` | `{success}` |
| `list_camera_presets` | GET | — | Array of preset rows |
| `save_camera_preset` | POST | `name`, `config` (JSON) | `{success}` |
| `update_camera_preset` | POST | `id`, `config` (JSON) | `{success}` |
| `list_takes` | GET | `animatic_id` | Array of take rows |
| `load_take` | GET | `take_id` | `{telemetry}` — full parsed telemetry array |
| `save_video` | POST | `animatic_id`, `telemetry` (JSON), `video` (blob), `mode` | `{success, video_id}` |

No external AI provider calls are made by this module. No PyAPI (FastAPI) calls are made.

`FramesManager::createMapRun()` is called internally in the `save_video` action to register the recording in the provenance tracking system.

---

## UI & Interaction

### Layout

The editor occupies the full viewport (`100vw × 100vh`) with `overflow: hidden`. The Three.js canvas is injected into the container. All UI chrome floats over the canvas:

- **Top centre** — version label (`SAGE Motion v6.4`)
- **Top left** — REC indicator (hidden unless recording)
- **Bottom left** — REPLAYING overlay (hidden unless replaying)
- **Top right** — `lil-gui` panel in a draggable `#gui-container` div

The page `<meta viewport>` sets `user-scalable=no` to prevent pinch-zoom interfering with the 3D controls on mobile.

### GUI Structure

```
Motion Director (lil-gui, width 320)
├── Camera & Controls
│   ├── Preset (dropdown), Load Preset, Save New, Update Current
│   ├── Pos X / Pos Y (Alt) / Pos Z  [.listen()]
│   ├── FOV (Zoom)  [.listen()]
│   ├── Allow Pan / Allow Rotate / Allow Zoom / Auto Spin
│   └── Constraints (sub-folder, closed by default)
│       ├── minPolar, maxPolar
│       └── minDist, maxDist
├── Global Environment
│   ├── Scroll Speed, Blur Strength, Ambient Light, Sun Light, Fog Color
│   └── Background Texture (sub-folder)
│       ├── bgBrightness, bgTint
│       └── repeatX, repeatY, offsetX, offsetY
├── Active Actor
│   ├── Select (layer dropdown), Role, 🖐 Drag & Drop Mode
│   ├── Transform (sub-folder)
│   │   ├── X, Y (Height), Z, Scale
│   │   ├── Z-Order (Sort), Parallax (Offset)
│   │   └── Pitch, Yaw, Roll
│   └── Physics & Material (sub-folder)
│       ├── Sway Amp, Sway Spd, Vibration, Self-Glow
└── System (open by default)
    ├── Load Replay (take dropdown), ► Play Take, ■ Stop Replay
    ├── Rec Mode (Video + Data / Data Only)
    ├── 🔴 Record
    └── 💾 Save Scenario
```

### Mobile Behaviour

The page is designed for full-screen use on Android/Chrome. Touch events are wired for GUI dragging (`touchstart`, `touchmove`, `touchend`). `OrbitControls` handles pinch/pan natively on mobile. The GUI width is fixed at 320px, which fits a typical Android screen in landscape or portrait with horizontal scroll.

### Toast / Alert Pattern

The module uses native `alert()` and `confirm()` dialogs for preset save confirmations and error messages. No custom toast system is used. The info label at the top changes to "UPLOADING..." in yellow during video upload and reverts on completion.

