## 1. Introduction

The Mail Hub is SAGE''s built-in email marketing and newsletter dispatch system, designed to let Sebastian send campaign emails to *The Anima Chronicles* subscriber audience directly from within the platform — without relying on third-party dashboard tools. It manages the full newsletter lifecycle from content authoring through scheduled delivery, handling per-recipient queue management, daily send-limit enforcement, and GDPR-conscious subscriber data handling. The system integrates with Brevo (formerly Sendinblue) as its primary delivery provider, with a zero-PII architecture that fetches subscriber email addresses just-in-time at send time and never stores them locally. A pluggable provider interface also supports direct SMTP delivery, making the module portable across hosting environments including Termux/Android.

---

## 2. Module Details

### Purpose & Scope

The Mail Hub handles everything needed to run an email newsletter operation at low or zero cost:

- **Authoring** — draft newsletter campaigns with HTML and plain-text body content
- **Templates** — reusable email wrapper layouts with a `{{content}}` injection tag
- **Scheduling** — set a future `scheduled_at` datetime; the scheduler worker respects it
- **Queue management** — per-recipient send jobs written to `mail_hub_queue`, processed in configurable batches
- **Provider management** — Brevo API and raw SMTP drivers, with per-provider daily send limits
- **Subscriber view** — live read-only window into Brevo contact list (no local PII stored)
- **Unsubscribe handling** — one-click unsubscribe tokens, propagated back to Brevo via API

**Pipeline position:** Post-production / audience engagement. The Mail Hub sits outside the core animation pipeline and operates as an independent publishing channel, parallel to the Cinemagic Hub (web magazine delivery). It is likely used for subscriber updates, episode release announcements, and campaign communications for TAC.

**Inputs:** Newsletter content (HTML/plain text), Brevo subscriber list, configured mail provider credentials.  
**Outputs:** Queued per-recipient send jobs → delivered emails via Brevo API or SMTP.

---

### Key Features

#### Dashboard
- Summary stat chips: total newsletters, emails sent in last 7 days, active subscriber count (live from Brevo), pending queue depth
- Recent campaigns table with status badges and send progress bars
- Quick-access "New Newsletter" button

#### Newsletters
- Full CRUD: create, edit, duplicate, delete (draft/cancelled only)
- Status lifecycle: `draft` → `scheduled` → `sending` → `sent` / `cancelled` / `failed`
- Per-newsletter override of sender name and sender email (falls back to provider defaults)
- Optional template wrapper selection per newsletter
- Optional provider override per newsletter (falls back to default provider)
- Inline send progress: `total_sent / total_recipients` with a visual fill bar and failed count
- Enqueue confirmation modal — one-click dispatch to queue all active subscribers
- Status filter + title/subject search with debounced input
- Paginated table (40 per page)

#### Templates
- Reusable HTML + plain-text email wrappers
- `{{content}}` placeholder tag is replaced with newsletter body at send time
- CRUD: create, edit, delete (delete NULLs `template_id` on linked newsletters to avoid orphans)
- In-modal HTML / Plain Text tab switcher

#### Subscribers
- Live read-only view pulled directly from Brevo API at page load
- No subscriber PII is stored in the local database
- Displays: email, name (from Brevo `FIRSTNAME`/`LASTNAME` attributes), status (active / unsubscribed), source, timestamps
- Status filter (active / unsubscribed)
- Paginated (50 per page, offset-based via Brevo API)
- GDPR info banner explaining the zero-PII architecture

#### Providers
- Add/edit/delete mail provider configurations
- Supported drivers: `brevo` (Brevo Transactional API) and `smtp` (raw socket SMTP)
- Driver-specific config fields rendered dynamically in the modal (API key for Brevo; host/port/user/pass for SMTP)
- Per-provider daily limit with auto-reset: `sent_today` resets on first send of a new calendar day
- Default provider flag (enforced single-default constraint)
- In-modal test send: saves provider config then fires a test email to a specified address
- Info panel explaining Brevo free tier (300 emails/day)

#### Queue Processing
- `enqueueNewsletter()` — fetches all active subscriber IDs from Brevo (paginated, 500 at a time), writes one `mail_hub_queue` row per recipient, sets newsletter status to `sending`
- `processBatch()` — batch processor (default 20 jobs per call); fetches live contact data from Brevo JIT per job, applies template wrapping, injects preview preheader spacer, injects per-recipient unsubscribe link, delivers via resolved provider driver
- Retry logic: up to `max_attempts` (default 3) before marking a job `failed`
- Daily limit enforcement: skips remaining jobs if provider limit reached; they stay `pending` and resume on the next scheduler run
- `finaliseSentNewsletters()` — automatically transitions a newsletter to `sent` when no `pending` or `processing` jobs remain
- Queue archive: completed rows (sent/failed/skipped) can be moved to `mail_hub_queue_archive` to keep the live queue table lean

#### Unsubscribe System
- Per-recipient, per-newsletter token generated at send time (`bin2hex(random_bytes(32))`)
- Token injected into email HTML as a footer link (`/mail_hub/unsubscribe.php?token=…`)
- `List-Unsubscribe` header added to every outbound message
- `unsubscribe()` in `MailHubManager` validates the token, calls Brevo API to blacklist the contact (`emailBlacklisted: true`), marks the token used, and logs an `unsubscribed` event

