INSERT INTO `documentations` (`id`, `name`, `description`, `desc_short`, `keywords`, `content`, `duration`, `type`, `category_id`, `target_collection`, `sort_order`, `is_active`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `regenerate_audios`, `active_map_run_id`) VALUES ('500', 'mod_generator_forge', NULL, NULL, NULL, '# SAGE Module: Generator Forge

**File:** `public/generator_forge.php`
**API:** `public/api/generator_forge_api.php`
**Data Model:** `generator_config`
**Doc Version:** 1.0 — SAGE 2.0 Alpha

---

## 1. Introduction

The Generator Forge is SAGE''s unified interface for authoring, managing, and executing AI content generators — reusable, schema-driven prompting units that power the automated analysis and creative generation pipelines throughout the platform. Each generator encapsulates a system role, a structured instruction set, a typed parameter schema, and a JSON output contract, allowing any part of the SAGE pipeline to invoke consistent, repeatable AI behaviour without re-engineering prompts from scratch. The Forge provides a world-class runner UI — a two-panel workspace combining a live parameter form with a multi-view result panel — and a full CRUD management layer for creating, editing, toggling, and duplicating generators. It sits at the foundation of SAGE''s AI integration layer, serving as the configuration registry that all downstream modules (VidBat, Auto-Narrative Lab, PLUSH, Fuzz Forge, and others) draw from when making AI calls.

---

## 2. Module Details

### Purpose & Scope

The Generator Forge serves two roles simultaneously:

**Registry:** It is the canonical store of all AI generator configurations in SAGE. Each record in `generator_config` is a complete, self-contained prompt program — system prompt, parameter definitions, output schema, and optional Oracle seeding. Any SAGE module that needs to call an AI model references a `config_id` from this registry.

**Runner:** It provides an interactive UI for executing generators on demand, previewing results in multiple formats, and iterating on configuration. It is the developer/showrunner''s workbench for prompt engineering within the SAGE ecosystem.

**Pipeline position:** The Generator Forge sits upstream of all automated AI pipelines. It is not itself a batch processor — it runs one generation at a time interactively. Batch invocations of generators (e.g. from VidBat or the sketch continuity enqueuer) call the same `generator_forge_api.php` `generate` route directly, bypassing the UI.

**Inputs:** Generator configurations (created/edited in the Forge UI), runtime parameter values (entered by the user in the params form), and optional Oracle creative seeds drawn from the WordNet dictionary system.

**Outputs:** Structured JSON responses from the configured AI model, surfaced in four display formats. Results are session-local only — there is no persistence of individual generation runs beyond the in-memory history stack.

---

### Key Features

#### Two-Panel Workspace

The main view divides into a left **Parameters Panel** (360px fixed, scrollable) and a right **Result Panel** (fills remaining width). On mobile/narrow screens these stack vertically. The workspace is hidden until a generator is selected from the sidebar; an empty-state prompt is shown otherwise.

#### Sidebar with Search and Area Filtering

The left sidebar lists all generators available to the current user. Generators can be filtered by **display area** (a tag system allowing generators to be grouped by pipeline context — e.g. "Curation", "Narrative", "KG") and searched by title with 200ms debounce. Each sidebar card shows the generator title, model badge, and optional `PUBLIC` / `⚙ Oracle` badges. An inline **toggle button** (play/pause icon) activates or deactivates a generator without opening the edit modal. An inline **duplicate button** (copy icon) clones the generator and immediately opens the clone for editing.

#### Dynamic Parameter Form

When a generator is selected, the params panel is populated from the `parameters` JSON field of the config. The form renderer supports:

| Parameter Type | Rendered As |
|---|---|
| `string` with `enum` | Pill button group (single-select) |
| `string` with `multiline: true` or `textarea: true` | Resizable textarea |
| `integer` / `number` | Number input with optional `min`/`max` |
| All other `string` | Text input |

Each field supports `label`, `placeholder`, `hint`/`description`, and `default` from the config schema.

#### FORGE Button (Generation)

The amber **FORGE** button submits the current parameter values to the `generate` API action. During generation, the button shows a spinner and is disabled. Keyboard shortcut: `Ctrl+Enter` / `Cmd+Enter`.

#### Multi-View Result Panel

After generation, results are displayed in four switchable tabs:

| Tab | Content |
|---|---|
| **Result** | Friendly view — surfaces a single `result`/`text`/`content`/`output`/`value`/`answer` key as formatted prose, or renders all string keys as labelled blocks with sub-objects as pretty-printed JSON |
| **Keys** | Flat key-value explorer with per-key copy buttons; nested objects are flattened up to depth 3 |
| **JSON** | Syntax-highlighted JSON tree |
| **Raw** | Verbatim AI response string |

The toolbar above the result shows:
- A **parse strategy badge** (`direct` / `stripped_fences` / `extracted_object` / `extracted_array` / `repaired` / `failed`) indicating how the response was decoded
- **Elapsed milliseconds** for the generation call
- A **Copy** button (copies content from the active tab) and an **Erase** button

#### Bulletproof JSON Parser

The API applies a six-stage parsing pipeline to every AI response:
1. Direct `json_decode`
2. Strip markdown code fences (` ```json … ``` `)
3. Regex-extract first balanced `{…}` object
4. Regex-extract first `[…]` array (wrapped as `{"items": […]}`)
5. Repair common AI mistakes: trailing commas, basic single-quote strings
6. Fail gracefully — return `null` data with `strategy: "failed"`, surface raw response in the Raw tab

#### Session History

Up to 50 prior generations are retained in a JavaScript in-memory array per page session. The **History** button (clock icon in the workspace header) opens a modal listing all runs with timestamp, generator title, and elapsed ms. Clicking a history entry re-renders that result in all four tabs without re-calling the API.

#### Create / Edit Generator Modal

The modal exposes the full generator config surface:

| Field | Notes |
|---|---|
| **Title** | Display name |
| **Sort Order** | Integer for sidebar list ordering (lower = first) |
| **Model** | Select populated from `AIProvider::getModelCatalog()` grouped by provider |
| **Display Areas** | Multi-select — links generator to one or more display area categories |
| **Config JSON** | Full raw JSON textarea — validated live on input; schema: `{ system: {role, instructions[]}, parameters: {}, output: {}, examples: [] }` |
| **Public** | Admin-only flag; public generators are visible to all users |
| **Active** | Toggle generator availability |
| **Creative Oracle** | Optional section (see Oracle below) |

Live JSON validation runs on every keystroke in the config textarea, showing a green `✓ Valid JSON` or red `✕ Invalid JSON` hint inline.

#### Creative Oracle Integration

Generators can be linked to one or more WordNet dictionaries via the **Oracle Config** section of the edit modal. When a generator with `oracle_config` is executed:

1. `\App\Oracle\Bloom` samples `num_words` lemmas from the specified dictionaries
2. An error-rate parameter introduces controlled noise/variation
3. The sampled word list is injected into the system message as an `INSPIRATIONAL HINT` block, seeding thematic and tonal variety into the AI output

Oracle config is stored as JSON in the `oracle_config` column. Dictionaries are loaded via `\App\Dictionary\DictionaryManager`.

---

### Data Model

#### Primary Table: `generator_config`

| Column | Type | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `id` | `int` AUTO_INCREMENT | Internal PK |
| `config_id` | `varchar(255)` UNIQUE | Stable string identifier used by other modules (e.g. `auto_curator_v1`) |
| `user_id` | `int` nullable | `NULL` = system/public generator; otherwise owner |
| `title` | `varchar(255)` | Display name |
| `model` | `varchar(255)` | Model string passed to `AIProvider` (e.g. `claude-fast`, `openai/gpt-oss-120b`) |
| `system_role` | `text` | System prompt role declaration |
| `instructions` | `longtext` JSON | Array of instruction strings prepended to user input |
| `parameters` | `longtext` JSON | Parameter schema keyed by field name (see Dynamic Parameter Form above) |
| `output_schema` | `longtext` JSON | JSON Schema object describing expected output shape |
| `examples` | `longtext` JSON nullable | Few-shot examples array |
| `oracle_config` | `longtext` JSON nullable | `{ dictionary_ids: [], num_words: int, error_rate: float }` |
| `active` | `tinyint(1)` | `1` = available for use |
| `is_public` | `tinyint(1)` | `1` = visible to all users (admin-set only) |
| `list_order` | `int` | Sidebar sort order |
| `created_at` / `updated_at` | `datetime` | Timestamps |

No ChromaDB/vector store interaction. The Generator Forge operates purely over MariaDB.

#### Repository Class

`src/Service/GeneratorRepository.php` — PDO-only, no Doctrine. Provides:
- `listForUser(userId, filterArea, search)` — filtered list query
- `findById(id)` → generator record object with `toArray()`
- `findActiveForUser(configId, userId)` → resolves by `config_id` string
- `createFromConfigJson(...)` / `updateFromConfigJson(...)`
- `toggleActive(id)` → returns new boolean state
- `duplicate(id, userId)` → clones record with `"Copy of …"` title
- `updateOrder(ids[])` → bulk `list_order` update
- `getAllDisplayAreas()` → area tag records [VERIFY: table name for display areas]

---

### API / Backend Integration

All UI actions are routed through a single endpoint:

**`POST /api/generator_forge_api.php`** — JSON body with `action` key.

| Action | Description |
|---|---|
| `list` | List generators for current user, with optional `filter_area` and `search` |
| `get` | Fetch full generator record by `id` |
| `get_info` | Return config metadata (params, output schema) without AI call — for external callers |
| `create` | Create new generator record |
| `update` | Update existing record |
| `delete` | Delete (owner or admin only) |
| `toggle` | Toggle `active` flag; returns `{ ok, active, message }` |
| `copy` | Duplicate generator; returns `{ new_id }` |
| `update_order` | Save drag-drop sort order (array of ids) |
| `get_areas` | Return all display area records |
| `get_models` | Return model catalog from `AIProvider::getModelCatalog()` grouped by provider, with default model |
| `get_dictionaries` | Return all dictionaries from `DictionaryManager` (for Oracle select) |
| `generate` | Execute generator: build system+user messages → call `AIProvider::sendMessage()` → parse response → return structured result |

**AI provider:** `$spw->getAIProvider()->sendMessage($model, $messages, $options)` — abstracted via `\App\Core\AIProvider`. The model string in `generator_config.model` is passed directly; the provider class handles routing to the appropriate upstream API (Anthropic, OpenAI, etc.).

**WordNet PyAPI:** Referenced via `$GLOBALS[''WORDNET_PYAPI_URL'']` (default `http://127.0.0.1:8009`), but direct HTTP calls to the PyAPI are made within `\App\Oracle\Bloom`, not in the API file itself. [VERIFY: whether Bloom uses the PyAPI endpoint or queries the WordNet DB directly]

**No FastAPI calls** are made by the Generator Forge itself. It is a pure MariaDB + `AIProvider` module.

---

### UI & Interaction

#### Layout

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  ⚗ GENERATOR FORGE          [stat] [+] [gear]        │  ← Header (52px)
├──────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────┤
│  Search              │                               │
│  [All][Area][Area…]  │   (empty: Select a Generator) │
│  ─────────────────── │                               │
│  ▸ Generator Title   │   ┌── Workspace ─────────────┐│
│    [model] [PUBLIC]  │   │ Title  [active] [model]  ││
│    [⧉ dup] [▶ tog]   │   │ [History] [Edit]         ││
│  ▸ Generator Title   │   ├── Params ──┬── Result ───┤│
│    ...               │   │ form…     │ [tabs…]      ││
│                      │   │           │ result body  ││
│                      │   ├──────────-│              ││
│                      │   │[FORGE][⧉][✕]│            ││
│                      │   └──────────┴──────────────┘│
└──────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────┘
```

**Desktop** (>900px): sidebar (300px) + workspace with params (360px fixed) + result (flex).
**Tablet** (768–900px): sidebar collapses to top, workspace stacks params above result.
**Mobile** (<768px): sidebar becomes a horizontal scroll strip (max-height 220px), workspace is single-column.

#### Viewport Scaling

When loaded standalone (`generator_forge.php`), `<meta viewport>` sets `initial-scale=0.9`. When embedded inside the Floatool iframe (`?embed=1`), scale is set to `1.0` (parent zoom already handles sizing).

#### Toast Notifications

Four-type toast system (`success` / `error` / `info`) rendered in a fixed bottom-right container. Auto-dismiss after 3 seconds (1.5s for copy confirmations). Click to dismiss early.

#### Modals

- **History Modal** — 500px max-width; lists session generations; Clear All button
- **New/Edit Generator Modal** — 680px max-width; full config form; live JSON validation; Oracle section collapsible by visual separation; Delete button (danger, owner/admin only)

Both modals close on overlay click or `Escape` key.

---

### Dependencies & Related Modules

| Dependency | Role |
|---|---|
| `\App\Core\SpwBase` | Application singleton — provides PDO, `AIProvider`, file logger, paths |
| `\App\Core\AIProvider` | Upstream AI call abstraction; provides `sendMessage()` and `getModelCatalog()` |
| `\App\Service\GeneratorRepository` | PDO repository for `generator_config` CRUD |
| `\App\Dictionary\DictionaryManager` | Provides dictionary list for Oracle config select |
| `\App\Oracle\Bloom` | Creative seeding engine; invoked during `generate` when `oracle_config` is set |
| `AccessManager` | Session authentication gate |
| `generator_admin.php` | **Legacy parallel admin** — manages the same `generator_config` table via a different interface; the Forge was built as a non-destructive replacement. A header link points back to the classic admin. |
| `/js/sage-home-button.js` | SAGE universal home/back nav button |

**Modules that consume Generator Forge configs (via `config_id`):**

The following modules call `generator_forge_api.php?action=generate` (or equivalent) using `config_id` strings registered in the Forge:

- **Auto-Narrative Laboratory** — uses curation and semantic generators (`auto_curator_v1`, `md_curator_v1`, etc.)
- **VidBat** — sketch curation pipeline (`auto_curator_v1`, `sketch_sequence_curator_v1`, `sketch_tag_extractor_v1`)
- **Fuzz Forge / KG Import Bridge** — entity enrichment generators (`md_filter_entity_enricher_v1`, `filter_query_enricher_v1`)
- **PLUSH Editor** — narrative beat analysis (`narrative_beat_analyst_v1`, `narrative_episode_composer_v1`, `narrative_episode_synthesiser_v1`)
- **Writers Room / Narrative Architect** — structural analysis (`wroom_architect_v1`)
- **Overlay/Localisation tools** — caption generation (`overlay_text_composer_en_v1`, `overlay_text_translator_v1`)

---

### Seeded Generator Configs (from DB export)

The following generators are present in the 2.0 alpha database, illustrating the range of use cases:

| config_id | Title | Model | Public |
