## 1. Introduction

The SAGE DAW is a browser-based multitrack audio workstation built into the SAGE platform, designed to sequence, mix, and export audio stems directly within the animated series production pipeline. It sits at the intersection of the Editorial and Audio systems: when launched from the Paradigm B dialogue spotting editor for a specific shot, it automatically pre-populates timeline lanes with every audio stem linked to that shot (ambiences, cues, foley, FX sounds, themes, and dialogue renders), and docks the shot''s source video above the timeline for frame-accurate lip-sync reference. Each track supports per-clip waveform display via WaveSurfer.js v7, a non-destructive volume envelope editor, a per-track FX chain (Gain, Volume, Compressor, EQ 3-Band, Limiter) powered by Tone.js, and a master channel with the same plugin suite plus a stereo VU meter. Completed mixes are exported via an async PyAPI bounce endpoint that renders a full WAV mixdown using FFmpeg filtergraphs — translating every envelope, clip trim, track volume, and plugin chain into native FFmpeg syntax — then registers the resulting audio file in the `audios` table and links it back to the originating entity.

---

## 2. Module Details

### 2.1 Purpose & Scope

The DAW solves the problem of assembling and mixing the audio layer of a TAC shot entirely within SAGE, without requiring an external DAW application. Its primary use cases are:

- **Shot-mode:** launched from Paradigm B (`paradigm_b.php?scene_id=X&shot_id=Y`), auto-loads all audio stems and video for a single shot.
- **Freestanding mode:** accessed directly, browses any of the six audio entity types from the Asset Bin and assembles arbitrary compositions saved as named project files.

**Inputs:** `audios` records (via entity junctions), `editorial_shots` audio references, `editorial_shot_dialogues` → `audio_dialogue_lines` → `audios`.

**Outputs:** WAV mixdown registered in `audios` table; optionally linked to a `daw_shot_saves` or `daw_project_files` row.

---

### 2.2 Key Features

#### Asset Bin

Right-side flyout panel (`.bin-panel`). Displays audio entities from any of six tables: `audio_ambiences`, `audio_cues`, `audio_dialogue_lines`, `audio_foleys`, `audio_fxsounds`, `audio_themes`. The entity type is selected from a dropdown (entity list, 6 per page). Selecting an entity loads its associated `audios` records. Each audio asset shows a drag handle, a Howler.js preview play button, and a `+` button to add a new track lane + clip. Assets can also be dragged directly to the timeline or onto an existing clip to replace its audio.

#### Timeline / Track Lanes

The timeline canvas is a flexbox layout of `.daw-track` rows injected dynamically by JS. Each row has a sticky 150px track head (left panel) and a `.track-lane` drop zone (right). Clips are absolutely positioned `<div class="daw-clip">` elements inside the lane, with `left = startTime * masterZoom` and `width = duration * masterZoom`.

**Track head** has three dot-tab panels:
- **Main** — track name, color strip, Solo (S) / Mute (M) buttons, volume slider.
- **Envelope** — view select (Waveform / Envelope) that switches the WaveSurfer instance between `interact:false` and `interact:true` + EnvelopePlugin mode.
- **Track FX** — opens a full-screen Track FX modal with plugin chain + parameter UI.

#### Clip Operations

- **Drag-to-move** — pointer/mouse events on clip body, constrained to start ≥ 0, snaps to grid if snap is enabled.
- **Cut mode** — click on clip splits it at the click point. Both halves are independent clips; left clip retains duration, right clip gets a `trimStart` offset so the audio file plays from the correct position.
- **Remove mode** — click on clip deletes it immediately.
- **Drag-from-bin onto clip** — replaces the clip''s audio source while preserving envelope points and start time.
- **Clip header ×** — removes clip.

#### Waveform Display (WaveSurfer.js v7)

Each clip instantiates a `WaveSurfer.create()` instance inside its `.clip-ws` container. The container width is `fullDuration * masterZoom` and the clip element''s visible width is `duration * masterZoom`. For trimmed clips, `translateX(-(trimStart * masterZoom)px)` scrolls the waveform so the visible window aligns with the audible portion. `ws.zoom(masterZoom)` is called on ready and whenever zoom changes.

#### Envelope Editor (WaveSurfer Envelope Plugin)

Switching a track to "Envelope" view destroys and recreates the WaveSurfer instance with `interact:true` and `EnvelopePlugin` registered at creation time (required for SVG touch/mouse events to work). Point coordinates are synced back to `clip.envelopePoints` on pointer-up and on a 500ms polling interval. Switching back to "Waveform" recreates with `interact:false`, preserving the points array. Envelope points survive clip save/load and are passed to the bounce engine for rendering.

#### Playback Engine

RAF loop in `daw-playback.js`. On each frame, increments `STATE.curTime` by elapsed wall-clock delta (not audio clock). For each clip: if `curTime` is within `[startTime, startTime+duration)`, calls `ws.seekTo(audioTime / fullDuration)` then `ws.play()`; outside that window, calls `ws.pause()`. Playhead is rendered via CSS `transform: translateX(curTime * masterZoom)` from a fixed `left: var(--track-head-w)` base. The timeline auto-scrolls when the playhead reaches 85% of the viewport width.

If Tone.js is available, `Tone.start()` is triggered on first play to unlock the AudioContext.

#### Master Channel & Track FX (Tone.js)

All audio routing goes through a Tone.js signal chain when Tone is available. Each track has `inputNode (Gain) → [optional fx chain] → outNode (Gain) → MASTER.inputNode`. Clips are connected via `createMediaElementSource(mediaElement)` bridging WaveSurfer''s underlying `<audio>` element into the Tone graph.

**Available plugins (both track and master):** Gain, Volume, Compressor (Web Audio API), EQ 3-Band (Tone.EQ3), Limiter (Tone.Limiter). Each plugin''s parameter state is stored in `PLUGIN_STATE` / `track.pluginState` and serialized with the project save.

Master channel modal shows a stereo VU meter (two Canvas elements, RAF-animated via `Tone.Meter`).

#### Bounce to WAV (PyAPI)

Triggered by the "Bnc" menubar button. The flow:

1. **Client** serializes all clip URLs → unique set, fetches each as a `Blob`, builds a `FormData` with all audio files + `state_json`.
2. **Client** POSTs to `http://localhost:8009/daw/bounce-async`.
3. **PyAPI** (`daw_service.py`) saves files to a temp directory, spawns `render_bounce()` in a `BackgroundTask`, returns `{ status: "queued", task_id }`.
4. **Client** polls `GET /daw/status/{task_id}` every 1.5s; on `completed` calls `?api_action=register_bounce` (PHP).
5. **PHP** (`DawApi::registerBounce`) moves the `bounce_{taskId}.wav` from `services_data/daw_renders/` to `public/audios/`, claims the next `audio_counter` ID, inserts into `audios`, and optionally inserts into `audios_2_{entity_type}`.
6. A progress modal with a spinner and cancel button is shown throughout.

**FFmpeg filtergraph** (`daw_service.py::render_bounce`) translates the JS state into native FFmpeg:
- Per-clip: `atrim=start=trimStart:duration=duration,asetpts=PTS-STARTPTS,adelay=startMs`
- Envelope: builds a piecewise-linear `volume=eval=frame:volume=''if(lt(t-start,t_next),interp,…)''` expression matching the Tone.js EnvelopePlugin math.
- Track mix: `amix` with `normalize=0`.
- Per-track FX: `volume`, `acompressor`, `bass+equalizer+treble`, `alimiter` filters.
- Master mix + FX: same pattern.

#### Undo / Redo

In-memory stack in `daw-history.js` (max 100 entries). Tracked operations: add track, remove track, add clip, remove clip, move clip, replace clip audio, cut clip. Not tracked: volume, mute, solo, zoom, plugin params. Keyboard shortcuts: `Ctrl+Z` undo, `Ctrl+Y` / `Ctrl+Shift+Z` redo. Undo/redo buttons in menubar highlight amber when history is available.

#### Save / Load — Two Modes

**Shot saves** (`daw_shot_saves` table): named snapshots anchored to a specific `shot_id`. Shown in the top section of the merged Save/Load modal when in shot mode. Save/overwrite/load/delete per entry.

**Freestanding projects** (`daw_projects` + `daw_project_files`): named project folders with one or more named save files per folder. Shown in the bottom section of the same modal.

Both serialize/deserialize via `serializeDawState()` / `deserializeDawState()` which capture `PROJECT` settings, `MASTER` FX chain + plugin state, all tracks (name, color, vol, muted, solo, envelopeMode, fxChain, pluginState), and all clips (trackId, url, name, startTime, trimStart, duration, envelopePoints). Envelope mode per track is additionally stored in `localStorage`.

#### Shot Video Player

In shot/scene mode, a docked video panel renders above the menubar at up to `40dvh`. The `<video>` element is wired to the DAW transport: `play` → `dawPlay()`, `pause` → `dawPause()`, `seeked` → `seekTimeline(vid.currentTime)`. A **Float** button (🖼 Vid) moves the video to a draggable, resizable floating modal (`.fv-modal`) with pointer drag on titlebar and pointer resize on bottom-right corner handle. Docking back moves the video element back to the docked container.

#### Ruler & Grid

Ruler: HTML5 Canvas drawn by `drawRuler()` — bar numbers (amber), beat ticks (dimmed lines). Width = `projectDuration * masterZoom`.

Grid: CSS `background-image` repeating tile generated by an in-memory Canvas at `pxPerBar()` width. Bar lines get full opacity, beat lines get 55%, subdivision lines get 30% (hidden below 5px/div). Color and opacity configurable in Project Settings modal. Position offset: `backgroundPosition: ${TRACK_HEAD_W}px 0` so the grid starts at the audio lane edge.

#### Project Settings Modal

Controls BPM (20–300), time signature (numerator 1–16, denominator 2/4/8/16), grid division (1/1 to 1/32), grid visibility toggle, snap-to-grid toggle, grid color (10-swatch picker), grid opacity (5–80%). Applied live to ruler, grid, and `snapTime()` calculations.

#### Zoom

`STATE.masterZoom` (pixels per second, default 80). Slider in the menubar (removed from header in final layout). Pinch-to-zoom supported on touch devices via `touchstart`/`touchmove` calculating distance between two fingers. On zoom change, all clip `left` and `width` values are recalculated, WaveSurfer instances are re-zoomed, and the ruler/grid are redrawn.

