**File:** `sage_module_plush.md`
**Module Files:** `plush.php`, `plush_api.php`, `plunar.php`
**Module Family:** Story Architecture / Beat Assembly
**SAGE 2.0 Documentation — Alpha Reference**

---

## 1. Introduction Paragraph

The PLUSH Editor (PLot Us Story Highlights) is SAGE''s primary beat assembly board for rapid story architecture. It operates as a dedicated drafting layer that sits cleanly above the platform''s image inference and public-facing content pipelines: PLUSH works exclusively on copies, leaving `sketches.description` fields (used for AI image generation prompts) and `sketch_overlay_texts` (surfaced in the Magazine Hub and other public-facing views) completely untouched until the author explicitly promotes content via the PluNar bridge. Stories in PLUSH are organised into scenes, which contain labelled groups of free-text highlight blocks; each block can be colour-coded, reordered by drag-and-drop, and tagged with entity references drawn from the platform''s characters, factions, locations, animas, sketches, and knowledge graph nodes. The companion **PluNar** module provides a bidirectional migration bridge between PLUSH Stories and Narrative Sequences, enabling a non-destructive round-trip workflow: sequences can be imported into PLUSH for narrative reworking, and PLUSH stories can be promoted back into the sequencer — with explicit conflict resolution for any sketch overlay texts that would be overwritten.

---

## 2. Module Details

### Purpose & Scope

PLUSH is a story drafting and beat architecture tool. Its defining design constraint is **non-interference**: it operates on its own isolated table family (`plush_*`) and does not write to `sketches.description` or `sketch_overlay_texts` during normal use. This allows a showrunner to freely draft, restructure, and iterate on beat content without risking corruption of the source-of-truth data that downstream systems (image generation queue, Magazine Hub, Cinemagic viewer) depend on.

**Primary pipeline position:** Pre-production / story development → feeds into Narrative Sequencer via PluNar.

**Inputs:**
- Author-entered free text (highlight blocks)
- Entity references pulled from existing platform entities (`characters`, `factions`, `locations`, `animas`, `sketches`, `kg_nodes`)
- Optionally: imported Narrative Sequences (via PluNar)

**Outputs:**
- Structured beat data in `plush_*` tables
- JSON exports (per-block or full-story)
- Optionally: new Narrative Sequences and updated `sketch_overlay_texts` (via PluNar, with conflict resolution)

---

### Key Features

#### Story & Scene Management
- **Story list view** (`plush.php`, no `?id`): lists all stories with creation date; supports inline story deletion (with full cascade confirmation) and a modal for creating new stories with title and optional description.
- **Scene management**: scenes are ordered units within a story, each with a title and optional synopsis. New scenes can be added via prompt or a persistent bottom button. Scene order is displayed numerically.
- **Scene filter with autocomplete**: a navbar search input filters the workspace to matching scene blocks in real time; an autocomplete dropdown (populated from server-side PHP JSON) allows keyboard navigation and selection by scene title, number, or ID.

#### Highlight Blocks
- **Free-text textarea blocks** with auto-resize on input.
- **Inline debounced save** (500ms) — saves to `plush_highlight_blocks` on every keystroke without an explicit save action.
- **Block colour coding**: six preset RGBA background colours plus a reset; colour is stored in `bg_color` on the block row and applied via `!important` inline style.
- **Drag-and-drop reorder**: full HTML5 drag API plus pointer-event fallback for mobile touch. On drop, `reorder_blocks` API call updates `display_order` for both English and translation variants atomically with negative-index staging to avoid constraint collisions.
- **Collapsed preview mode**: individual blocks can be collapsed to a single-line preview (first 50 chars); a global "Collapse All / Expand All" toggle in the navbar collapses or expands every block in the workspace.
- **Per-block JSON export**: downloads a single block''s content, scene context, and entity tags as a `.json` file.
- **Full-story JSON export**: exports all visible blocks (respecting the active scene filter) as a structured JSON payload including story metadata, language, filter state, and timestamp.
- **Block reference labels**: each block displays a `[scene_id . group_id . display_order]` reference badge for debugging and cross-referencing.

#### Groups
- Named groups provide sub-scene organisation. Groups have a drag-and-drop handle for reordering within a scene, an editable label (auto-saved with 600ms debounce), and a delete action that cascades to contained blocks.
- An **ungrouped / default group** (`group_id = 0`) is always present at the top of each scene.
- Inline "add block" and "add group" rows appear between every element, enabling insertion at any position without scrolling.

#### Entity Tagging
Each highlight block supports polymorphic entity tags stored in `plush_highlight_block_entities`. The tagging UI provides:

| Tab | Entity Table |
|-----|-------------|
| Char | `characters` |
| Fac | `factions` |
| Loc | `locations` |
| Anim | `animas` |
| Sket | `sketches` |
| KG | `kg_nodes` |

- Typeahead search with 280ms debounce; numeric queries also match by ID.
- Chips are colour-coded by entity type and display a clickable label that opens an entity detail iframe modal.
- Tags are stored with a cached `entity_label` at time of tagging.

#### Multilingual Support
- The `system_languages` table (shared platform resource) drives a language selector in the navbar.
- In non-English mode, the workspace enters a read-only structural state: drag handles, add/delete controls, and entity add rows are hidden via `.lang-not-en` CSS class on the workspace container.
- Translation blocks share the same `scene_id`, `group_id`, and `display_order` as their English counterparts but carry a different `language_code`. Reorder operations update both English and translation rows in a single transaction.
- A **System Languages modal** allows adding and removing languages (2-letter ISO codes); English (`en`) is protected from deletion.

#### Collections
PLUSH stories can be assigned to **Collections** (`plush_collections`), which are analogous to Cinemagics in the Narrative Sequencer. The collections panel supports:
- Assigning a story to an existing collection with an optional arc label
- Creating a new collection and immediately assigning the current story
- Removing story-collection assignments
- Panel collapse state is persisted to `localStorage`

---

### Data Model

#### Core PLUSH Tables

| Table | Purpose |
|-------|---------|
| `plush_stories` | Top-level story record (title, description) |
| `plush_scenes` | Ordered scenes within a story |
| `plush_highlight_groups` | Named groups within a scene |
| `plush_highlight_blocks` | Individual text blocks; one row per language variant |
| `plush_highlight_block_entities` | Polymorphic entity tags on blocks |
| `plush_collections` | Collection containers (analogous to `cinemagics`) |
| `plush_collections_2_stories` | Many-to-many story↔collection with `sort_order` and `arc_label` |
| `plush_story_dates` | In-universe timeline metadata per story (era label, sort values) |
| `plush_scene_dates` | In-universe timeline metadata per scene |

#### Referenced Platform Tables (read-only from PLUSH)

| Table | Used For |
|-------|---------|
| `system_languages` | Language selector and translation management |
| `characters`, `factions`, `locations`, `animas` | Entity tag autocomplete and chip display |
| `sketches` | Entity tag type "Sket"; also used extensively by PluNar |
| `kg_nodes` | Entity tag type "KG" |

#### Key Schema Notes
- `plush_highlight_blocks` stores one row **per language variant** of a block. The English row is the canonical record; translation rows share `scene_id`, `group_id`, and `display_order` but have a different `language_code`. There is no separate `overlay_id` — identity is by `(scene_id, group_id, display_order, language_code)`.
- `bg_color` is stored as a nullable `VARCHAR(30)` on `plush_highlight_blocks`; empty string is treated as NULL on save.
- Cascade deletes are enforced by FK constraints: deleting a story cascades to scenes → groups → blocks → entity tags.

---

### API / Backend Integration

All PLUSH CRUD is handled by `plush_api.php` via `fetch()` POST with `URLSearchParams`. There are no PyAPI (FastAPI) calls in this module. All operations are synchronous PHP/MariaDB.

#### `plush_api.php` Actions

| Action | Method | Description |
|--------|--------|-------------|
| `create_story` | POST | Insert new story |
| `delete_story` | POST | Full cascade delete of story and all children |
| `add_scene` | POST | Append scene to story |
| `add_group` | POST | Append group to scene |
| `delete_group` | POST | Delete group and its blocks |
| `update_group_label` | POST | Debounced label save |
| `add_block` | POST | Append EN block to scene/group |
| `update_block` | POST | Save block text (EN or translation upsert) |
| `update_block_color` | POST | Save `bg_color` |
| `delete_block` | POST | Delete all language variants at a given `(scene_id, group_id, display_order)` |
| `reorder_blocks` | POST | Atomic reorder with negative-index staging for translation rows |
| `add_block_entity` | POST | Tag a block with an entity; fetches and caches label |
| `remove_block_entity` | POST | Delete tag by `id` |
| `get_block_entities` | GET | Fetch all tags for a block (used after tag add to refresh chips) |
| `search_entities` | GET | Typeahead search across any allowed entity table |
| `create_collection` | POST | Create new collection |
| `assign_to_collection` | POST | Upsert story↔collection assignment |
| `remove_from_collection` | POST | Delete assignment |
| `get_languages` / `save_language` / `delete_language` | GET/POST | System language CRUD (shared with Cinemagic Editor) |

