---

## 1. Introduction

The Cinemagic Hub is SAGE''s magazine-style publishing system, responsible for assembling the platform''s AI-generated narrative sequences into polished, web-ready reading experiences. It organises content through a three-tier hierarchy — **Series → Cinemagics (Seasons) → Narrative Sequences (Episodes)** — and provides the full toolchain to author, preview, export, and deploy that content as standalone static HTML sites. Within the SAGE production pipeline the Hub sits at the final presentation layer: it consumes the frames, overlays, and sequences built upstream in the Sketch, Frame, and Cinemagic Editor modules, then renders them into cinematic scroll-readers complete with episode navigation, multilingual text, cover imagery, SEO metadata, social links, and PDF download options. Finished series can be exported as self-contained ZIP archives, rolled out directly to a GitHub Pages repository via a Forge Job, or previewed in-browser without leaving the SAGE interface.

---

## 2. Module Details

### Purpose & Scope

The Cinemagic Hub converts SAGE''s internal production database into publishable, audience-facing digital magazines. It handles the complete authoring and deployment lifecycle for a magazine series:

- **Authoring** — create and configure Series records, attach Cinemagic seasons, set cover imagery, templates, SEO fields, supported languages, and episode-level metadata.
- **Preview** — render any series landing page or individual episode as live HTML inside the SAGE interface without touching the public filesystem.
- **Export** — package a series as a portable ZIP (HTML + assets) for offline or CDN hosting.
- **Rollout** — write the same HTML + assets directly into a local Git repository and queue a `github_sync` Forge Job to push to GitHub Pages.
- **PDF Export** — submit a per-episode PDF generation job to the PyAPI, poll for completion, and store the resulting PDFs permanently under `public/media/magazines/series_{id}/`.

**Inputs:** Narrative Sequences, Sketches, Frames (with filenames), Sketch Overlay Texts, Sequence Overlay Texts, System Languages, Cinemagics.

**Outputs:** HTML episode pages, HTML series landing pages, sidecar JS data files, PDF issues (via PyAPI), ZIP archives, GitHub Pages rollouts.

---

### Key Features

**Series Manager Dashboard**
The Hub opens on a cover-grid dashboard showing all published magazines. Each card links to a live preview (`api.php?action=preview_series`). The left sidebar lists all series (draft and published) with status badges; clicking any entry opens the series editor in the main panel.

**Series Editor**
A form-based editor for the `cinemagic_series` record, including: title, status (`draft` / `published` / `archived`), sort order, cover image URL (with frame picker), magazine template (`default` / `hero_backdrop`), SEO keywords and description, supported languages (checkboxes, always includes `en`), asset URL prefix for CDN hosting, landing page script name override, and a synopsis textarea. On save the editor also manages the list of attached Cinemagics (seasons), allowing assignment and removal via the `cinemagic_series_2_cinemagics` pivot.

**Episode Metadata Modal**
Per-episode (per-Cinemagic × per-Sequence) metadata is edited in a bottom-sheet modal: episode cover image (with frame picker), SEO keywords, SEO description, and a dynamic social/newsletter links list (Instagram, YouTube, Facebook, Twitter/X, Newsletter). Defaults to three pre-set social links if none exist.

**Asset Frame Picker**
A bottom-sheet component that lets the user browse Sequences or Cinemagics, then select an individual frame image as the cover for a series or episode. Supports text search, paginated container list (12 items/page), and single-select grid of frame thumbnails.

**Two Magazine Templates**

| Template key | Behaviour |
|---|---|
| `default` | Classic centered layout — cover image at top, title, description, episode TOC list |
| `hero_backdrop` | Cinematic immersive layout — cover image fixed full-screen behind content with a dark gradient overlay; episode TOC on top |

Both templates include a language picker, episode navigation pills, prev/next buttons, and a fixed `top-actions` bar (newsletter link, share button, PDF download, language toggle).

**Multilingual Publishing**
All HTML renders (`renderSeriesIndexHtml`, `renderEpisodeHtml`) accept a `$langCode` parameter and an `$availableLangs` array. Overlay texts fall back to English if no translation exists for the chosen language. Language suffixes (`_de.html`, `_pt.html`) are appended to episode and landing page filenames in exports. The system language registry (`system_languages` table) is managed directly from the Hub sidebar or from `cinemagic_editor.php`.

**Episode Reader (`renderEpisodeHtml`)**
Each episode renders as a full cinematic vertical-scroll HTML page using the Cinzel + Lora font pairing and a dark filmic aesthetic. Features include: episode cover image with animated scroll indicator, panel-by-panel frame images with IntersectionObserver fade-in, overlay text blocks, a collapsible episode navigation bar fixed to the bottom, a `FIN` end mark, an end-of-episode teaser box (next episode or random-series picker with client-side randomisation for static exports), and a social icons row. Google Analytics (`G-SBSTRVS0NR`) is injected for non-preview renders.

**PDF Export Workflow**
1. User selects a PyAPI base URL (persisted in `localStorage`), an episode, and languages.
2. `submitPdfJobToPyAPI()` in `CinemagicHubManager` collects all frame images from the filesystem, assembles a raw `multipart/form-data` body (with `job_meta` JSON + image binaries), and POSTs to `/magazine-pdf/submit` on PyAPI via cURL.
3. The DB job row is created in `magazine_pdf_jobs` with status `pending`.
4. The frontend polls `/magazine-pdf/status/{job_id}` every 3 seconds and calls `update_pdf_job_status` to sync the DB row.
5. On `done`, `fetchAndStorePdfJob()` downloads the result ZIP from PyAPI, extracts the PDFs to `public/media/magazines/series_{id}/`, and calls the PyAPI cleanup endpoint.

**GitHub Pages Rollout**
`rolloutSeries()` writes all episode HTML files, sidecar JS data files (`data/ep_{id}.js`), the series index HTML, and all referenced image assets to a local directory within `GITPAGES_REPO_PATH` (env var, defaults to a Termux home path). It then enqueues a `forge_jobs` record of type `github_sync` with full push configuration.

**ZIP Export**
`exportSeriesZip()` produces the identical file set as the rollout but packages them into a temporary ZIP file served as a direct download. Assets are deduplicated via a `$copiedAssets` tracking array. PDFs already stored locally are bundled. A sidecar JS data file (`data/ep_{id}.js`) is included per episode per language for potential headless/SPA usage.

**System Languages Manager**
A bottom-sheet modal accessible from the sidebar allows adding and deleting 2-letter language codes. English (`en`) is the protected main language and cannot be deleted.

---

### Data Model

#### Tables read and written

| Table | Role |
|---|---|
| `cinemagic_series` | Primary series record: title, status, cover, template, SEO, supported languages, sort order |
| `cinemagic_series_2_cinemagics` | Pivot linking series to Cinemagics (seasons), with `sort_order` |
| `cinemagics` | Cinemagic (season) records |
| `cinemagics_2_sequences` | Pivot linking Cinemagics to Narrative Sequences; carries `chapter_label`, `cover_image_url`, `seo_keywords`, `seo_description`, `social_links` (JSON) |
| `narrative_sequences` | Episode/sequence records; `sequence_data` is a JSON array of `{sketch_id, frame_id}` objects |
| `sketches` | Scene/shot entities providing description fallback text |
| `frames` | Individual AI-generated images with `filename` paths |
| `frames_2_sketches` | Pivot mapping frames to their parent sketches (for latest-frame lookup) |
| `sketch_overlay_texts` | Per-sketch, per-language narrative text blocks with `display_order` |
| `sequence_overlay_texts` | Per-sequence, per-language title and description overrides |
| `system_languages` | Registry of supported ISO 639-1 language codes |
| `magazine_pdf_jobs` | Async PDF export job tracking: series, sequence, languages, status, error |
| `forge_jobs` | Shared job queue; used to enqueue `github_sync` rollout jobs |
| `cinemagic_hub_posts` | Legacy/alternate post type table (defined in schema, not actively used by current Hub views) [VERIFY: usage status] |

#### Key schema notes

- `cinemagic_series.template` — `''default''` or `''hero_backdrop''`
- `cinemagics_2_sequences.social_links` — JSON array of `{type, url}` objects (types: `instagram`, `youtube`, `facebook`, `twitter`, `newsletter`)
- `narrative_sequences.sequence_data` — JSON array; elements can be bare integers (legacy, sketch ID) or objects `{sketch_id: N, frame_id: M}`
- `magazine_pdf_jobs.status` — ENUM `pending | processing | done | error`

---

### API / Backend Integration

#### Internal API (`public/cinemagic_hub/api.php`)

All frontend AJAX calls POST to `api.php` with an `action` field. Key actions:

| Action | Description |
|---|---|
| `get_series_list` | Returns id, title, status for sidebar |
| `get_series_details` | Returns full series row + attached seasons |
| `save_series` | INSERT or UPDATE `cinemagic_series` |
| `delete_series` | DELETE series record (seasons/episodes not deleted) |
| `assign_season` / `remove_season` | Manage `cinemagic_series_2_cinemagics` pivot |
| `get_unassigned_seasons` | Cinemagics not yet attached to the series |
| `get_series_episodes` | Ordered episodes across all attached Cinemagics |
| `get_episode_meta` / `save_episode_meta` | Read/write `cinemagics_2_sequences` metadata columns |
| `search_sequences` / `search_cinemagics` | Paginated search for the asset picker |
| `get_sequence_frames` | Resolves frame image URLs for a sequence |
| `preview_series` | Renders and returns series index HTML directly |
| `preview_episode` | Renders and returns episode HTML directly |
| `export_series_zip` | Streams ZIP download |
| `rollout_series` | Writes to repo, queues Forge Job |
| `get_languages` / `save_language` / `delete_language` | System language CRUD |
| `submit_pdf_export_job` | Calls `CinemagicHubManager::submitPdfJobToPyAPI()` |
| `update_pdf_job_status` | Frontend polling sync; triggers `fetchAndStorePdfJob()` on `done` |
| `get_pdf_jobs` | Returns last 20 jobs for a series |
| `get_published_magazines_for_local` | Dashboard cover grid (local path resolution) |
| `serve_image` | Safe file-serving proxy for local images by relative path |

#### PyAPI Integration

| Endpoint | Method | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `POST /magazine-pdf/submit` | multipart/form-data | Submit PDF generation job; receives `job_meta` JSON + image binaries; returns `{job_id}` |
| `GET /magazine-pdf/status/{job_id}` | — | Poll job status |
| `GET /magazine-pdf/download/{job_id}` | — | Download completed PDF ZIP |
| `DELETE /magazine-pdf/cleanup/{job_id}` | — | Free PyAPI disk space post-download |

PyAPI base URL is stored in `localStorage(''sage_pyapi_url'')` on the client and sent with each job submission. The `WORDNET_PYAPI_URL` env var (default `http://127.0.0.1:8009`) is also available for server-side calls.

#### Environment Variables

| Variable | Default | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `GITPAGES_REPO_PATH` | `/data/data/com.termux/files/home/www/gitpages/sg_showcase_01` | Local Git repo for rollouts |
| `GIT_BOT_NAME` | `Post Bot` | Git commit author name |
| `GIT_BOT_EMAIL` | `post-bot@example.invalid` | Git commit author email |
| `WORDNET_PYAPI_URL` | `http://127.0.0.1:8009` | PyAPI base URL (server-side) |

---

### UI & Interaction

**Layout** — Three-column shell: fixed 52px topbar, 280px collapsible sidebar (series list + nav), scrollable main content area. The sidebar transitions off-canvas on screens ≤960px via a hamburger toggle and overlay backdrop.

**Theme** — Forge UI dark/light theme via `localStorage(''spw_theme'')` and `data-theme` attribute on `<html>`. Inline theme-init script fires before first paint to prevent flash.

**Views** — Three named view states managed by `switchView()`:
- `view-dashboard` — published magazine cover grid
- `view-series-editor` — series form + assigned seasons panel
- `view-pdf-export` — PDF job submission and job list

**Bottom Sheets** — Three full-height modal sheets slide up from the bottom on mobile:
- Asset frame picker (tab between Sequences / Cinemagics)
- Language manager
- Episode metadata editor

**Toast Notifications** — `toast(msg, type)` appends styled `.toast` divs to a fixed `#toast-container` with a 3.5-second auto-remove. Types: `success`, `error`, `info`, `warn`.

**PDF Job Polling** — After submission the frontend sets a 3-second `setTimeout` chain that calls the PyAPI status endpoint, updates the DB row via `api.php`, re-renders the jobs list, and reschedules itself until the job reaches `done` or `error`.

**Episode Reader** — `renderEpisodeHtml()` outputs a fully self-contained HTML page using `IntersectionObserver` for progressive reveal (fade-in + translateY) of each panel image and text block. Episode nav bar is collapsible with a toggle button; on open, the active episode pill is scrolled into view. The language picker is a CSS-toggle dropdown anchored top-right.

**Responsive behaviour** — All editor card actions stack vertically on narrow screens. Form rows collapse to single-column. Bottom-sheet pickers are full-width with a drag handle bar.

---

