**File:** `sage_module_scene_kitchen.md`
**Source files:** `public/sceki/index.php`, `public/sceki/graph.php`, `public/sceki/api.php`, `public/sceki/KitchenChef.php`, `public/scene_kitchen.php`, `public/api/kitchen_ajax.php`, `src/SceneKitchen/KitchenChef.php`, `src/SceneKitchen/Ingredients/*.php`

---

## 1. Introduction Paragraph

The Scene Kitchen is SAGE''s generative scene assembly studio, where production-ready image generation prompts are composed by combining modular creative building blocks called *ingredients*. Rather than writing prompts manually, the operator selects from a curated library of sketch templates, character interactions, style profiles, visual vocabulary entries, and world entities, then drops them into a central "Pot" from which a configured AI generator cooks a unified scene description. The module supports saved recipes for repeatable prompt patterns, a Scene Continuity sub-system for enforcing character appearance consistency across generated sketches, and a Knowledge Graph Subpot mode that lets the operator inject structured lore from the SAGE knowledge graph directly into the prompt context. Scene Kitchen sits at the entry point of the generative pipeline, feeding newly created `sketches` records into the production queue for downstream image and video generation.

---

## 2. Module Details

### Purpose & Scope

Scene Kitchen solves the problem of prompt entropy — the difficulty of producing consistent, compositionally rich AI image prompts across thousands of generated frames without a structured input system. It provides a drag-and-drop assembly board where ingredient types are mixed, optionally enriched with knowledge graph lore context, and sent to a configured LLM generator to produce a final scene description. That description is then saved as a `sketches` record which other SAGE modules (VidBat, Enhanimaticism, the frame generation pipeline) pick up for image synthesis.

**Inputs:**
- Ingredient selections from `sketch_templates`, `interactions`, `style_profiles`, and entity tables (`characters`, `locations`, `vehicles`, `artifacts`, `anivoc_*`)
- Optional chef''s notes (freeform instructions)
- KG node selections from `kg_nodes` / `kg_node_items`
- Generator configuration IDs from `generator_config`
- Saved recipe payloads from `scene_kitchen_pots`

**Outputs:**
- A new row in `sketches` (name, description, description_raw)
- Rows in `sketch_ingredients` (flexible per-ingredient audit trail)
- A row in `meta_sketches` (rigid legacy compatibility row with generator revision snapshot)
- A row in `generator_config_history` if the generator config has changed since the last cook

---

### Key Features

**Ingredient Source Browser**
The left panel presents a tabbed ingredient grid covering fourteen source types: `Templates`, `Interactions`, `Styles`, `Characters`, `Locations`, `Vehicles`, `Artifacts`, `Expr`, `Light`, `Color`, `Motion`. Each tab fetches its ingredient set via `api.php?action=fetch_ingredients`. Templates support category filtering; Interactions support group filtering. A live search field filters visible cards client-side by label and keyword. Cards that are already in the Pot are highlighted with an amber border.

**The Pot (Drop Zone)**
The central panel contains the active ingredient assembly area. Ingredients are added by dragging from the grid (via a grab handle) or by tapping the `+` button on each card on mobile. The Pot renders each selected ingredient as a removable chip. A `Chef''s Notes` textarea allows freeform prompt instructions to be appended to the generated prompt. The Pot state is held in a JS array (`potItems`) and is serialised into the cook payload.

**Cook Scene**
Clicking *Cook Scene* (`action=cook`) sends the assembled ingredient list and chef''s notes to `api.php`. The backend hydrates each ingredient to extract its prompt segment, concatenates segments into a structured prompt, calls the configured LLM generator (`generator_config`), parses the AI response, optionally calls a separate name generator, then calls `KitchenChefV2::saveSketch()` to persist the result. The cook response returns `sketch_id`, `sketch_name`, and `description`.

**Auto Continuity**
A checkbox on the Pot footer enables Auto Continuity mode. When active, after a successful cook, the module automatically calls `action=run_continuity` using any `characters`-type ingredients in the pot. The continuity pipeline fetches full character descriptions from the `characters` table, constructs a rewrite prompt instructing the AI to integrate exact character appearances into the generated scene description, and saves the result back to the sketch. The continuity generator is separately configurable in Kitchen Settings.

**Manual Continuity Modal**
An explicit continuity panel (`action=run_continuity`) allows the operator to select characters by checkbox, paste or load a scene description, optionally link a sketch ID, and trigger a continuity rewrite on demand. The rewritten scene can be copied or saved directly back to the linked sketch (`action=save_continuity_result`).

**KG Subpot Panel**
The center panel''s second tab exposes a Knowledge Graph integration layer. A collapsible tree (sourced from `kg_api.php?action=fetch_tree`) allows browsing and selecting `kg_nodes` by category. Selected nodes are assembled into a `[Knowledge Graph Subplot]` prompt block via `action=kg_subpot_preview`, which also queries `kg_node_items` for inter-node relationships when `include_edges` is checked. The assembled KG block can be added to the main Pot as a special `_kg_subpot` ingredient type. A live preview displays the assembled KG context text before it is added.

**Mini Graph Modal (SkGraph)**
From a KG chip''s graph icon, or from the KG tree node panel, a full Sigma.js subgraph viewer opens inside a modal. The graph displays a configurable-hop neighbourhood around any focal node (1–4 hops), sourced from `action=fetch_mini_graph`. The graph supports ForceAtlas2 layout (auto-run, toggle), node drag, hover highlighting, click-to-open floating node panel, "Re-center here" (queries a new subgraph from the selected node), "View Details" (opens a Markdown-rendered node detail modal with back/forward navigation history), and "Add to Subpot" actions. Node detail content is fetched from `kg_api.php?action=get_node`.

**Saved Recipes**
The operator can save the current Pot (ingredients + chef''s notes) to `scene_kitchen_pots` via `action=save_recipe` and load it back later via `action=load_recipe`. The load recipe modal supports pagination. Recipes can be deleted (`action=delete_recipe`).

**Random Recipe**
The dice button (`action=random_recipe`) clears the current Pot and assembles a probabilistic combination of a sketch template (85% chance), interaction (60%), style profile (50%), a random Anivoc visual category entry (70%), and 1–N characters (40%, up to `maxChars` config). `maxChars` is configurable in Kitchen Settings.

**Recently Cooked**
The right panel shows the 8 most recently created sketches (`action=recent_sketches`). Clicking any entry loads its description into the Continuity modal''s scene description field for quick rewriting.

**Kitchen Settings Modal**
Persists to `localStorage`: description generator, name generator, continuity generator, max characters for random recipe, and auto-expand-on-drag preference. Generator selection is stored under keys `sk2_desc_gen`, `sk2_name_gen`, `sk2_cont_gen`.

---

### Data Model

| Table | Role |
|---|---|
| `sketches` | Primary output — one row per cooked scene |
| `sketch_ingredients` | Flexible audit trail — one row per ingredient per cook, plus generator config rows |
| `meta_sketches` | Rigid compatibility row — links sketch to template, interaction, and generator revision IDs |
| `generator_config` | LLM generator definitions (model, system role, instructions, parameters, oracle config) |
| `generator_config_history` | Immutable snapshot of generator config at cook time; used for reproducibility |
| `scene_kitchen_pots` | Saved recipe store — `name`, `ingredients_json`, `notes` |
| `sketch_templates` | Template ingredients — `active=1 AND entity_type=''sketches'' AND is_ingredient=1` |
| `interactions` | Interaction ingredients — `active=1 AND is_ingredient=1` |
| `style_profiles` | Style ingredients — `convert_result IS NOT NULL AND is_ingredient=1` |
| `characters`, `locations`, `vehicles`, `artifacts`, `anivoc_*` | Entity ingredient tables — `is_ingredient=1` |
| `kg_nodes` | KG nodes for Subpot selection and Mini Graph |
| `kg_node_items` | KG edges — used for relationship context in Subpot preview |
| `kg_categories` | KG folder hierarchy — used to build the tree picker |
| `frames` | Referenced by `action=fetch_visuals` in `kg_api.php` (not directly used by Kitchen UI) |
| `frames_2_sketches` | JOIN target for frame→sketch associations (used by `fetch_visuals`) |

**`sketch_ingredients` detail:**

| Column | Notes |
|---|---|
| `ingredient_type` | Type string: `sketch_template`, `interaction`, `style_profile`, entity table name, `_kg_subpot`, `generator_config_desc`, `generator_config_name` |
| `source_id` | FK to the source table row (NULL for `_kg_subpot` and generator meta rows) |
| `prompt_fragment` | Hydrated text segment or label |
| `snapshot_data` | JSON snapshot of the ingredient object at cook time |
| `sort_order` | Insertion order |

---

### API / Backend Integration

All Scene Kitchen v2 actions route through `public/sceki/api.php`. The legacy v1 actions route through `public/api/kitchen_ajax.php` (uses OOP `App\SceneKitchen` classes — see note below).

#### `public/sceki/api.php` — Action Reference

| Action | Method | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `fetch_ingredients` | POST | Returns ingredient list for a given `type` and optional `filters` |
| `kg_search` | POST | Searches `kg_nodes` by name/keywords |
| `kg_subpot_preview` | POST | Assembles KG subplot text from selected node IDs |
| `fetch_mini_graph` | POST | Returns nodes + edges for N-hop subgraph around `node_id` |
| `cook` | POST | Full cook pipeline — hydrate, prompt, generate, save sketch |
| `run_continuity` | POST | Rewrites scene description with character appearance integration |
| `save_continuity_result` | POST | Saves rewritten description back to a sketch |
| `get_sketch_desc` | POST | Fetches `description` for a sketch by ID |
| `recent_sketches` | POST | Returns 8 most recent sketches |
| `random_recipe` | POST | Returns a probabilistic ingredient set |
| `save_recipe` | POST | Saves current pot to `scene_kitchen_pots` |
| `list_recipes` | POST | Paginated list of saved recipes |
| `load_recipe` | POST | Loads a saved recipe by ID, re-hydrating labels |
| `delete_recipe` | POST | Deletes a saved recipe |

#### KG API

The Mini Graph modal calls `../kg_api.php` directly for:

| Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|
| `?action=fetch_tree` | Full KG tree (categories + nodes, no content) |
| `?action=get_node&id=N` | Single node with content and items (outgoing + incoming edges) |

#### AI Provider

The cook and continuity actions call `$spw->getAIProvider()->sendMessage(model, messages, params)` — the platform''s unified AI provider abstraction. No direct HTTP calls to AI APIs are made from this module; routing to Groq, Pollinations, or other providers is handled by the provider layer.

#### Oracle / Bloom

If a `generator_config` row has an `oracle_config` JSON field with `dictionary_ids`, the cook action invokes `App\Oracle\Bloom::generateHint()` to sample creative seed words and appends them as an `INSPIRATIONAL HINT` block in the system message. This is non-fatal if the Oracle class is unavailable.

---

### UI & Interaction

**Layout:** Three-column on desktop — left ingredient panel (260px), center pot/KG panel (flex), right recent sketches panel (300px). A 50px header spans the full width. The body scrolls are contained within each panel; the outer layout is `overflow: hidden`.

**Mobile:** At ≤768px the grid collapses to a single column stack: ingredient panel (max 220px, scrollable) → center → right panel (max 280px). The original v1 (`public/scene_kitchen.php`) uses a bottom-drawer Pot pattern instead; the v2 (`public/sceki/index.php`) uses the three-column layout exclusively.

**Drag & Drop:** SortableJS handles ingredient cards. The left grid operates as a clone source (`pull: ''clone'', put: false`) restricted to the grab handle. The Pot drop zone accepts drops from the grid and supports internal re-ordering. On mobile, a `+` tap button on each card bypasses drag entirely.

**Toasts:** `Forge.toast(message, type, ms)` displays ephemeral notifications (success/error/info) bottom-right with auto-dismiss.

**Modals:** Standard Forge modal overlay pattern (`forge-modal-overlay` / `.open`). Active modals: Continuity, Config, Save Recipe, Load Recipe, Mini Graph (SkGraph), Node Details (SkGraph).

**Theme:** Supports dark (default) and light themes via `data-theme` attribute and `localStorage(''spw_theme'')`. Theme is applied before first paint by an inline script to prevent flash.

**KG Tree Fold State:** Open/closed folder states in the KG tree are persisted to `localStorage` under key `sk2_kg_tree_open` and restored on re-render (unless a search filter is active, in which case all matches are shown expanded).

---

### Dependencies & Related Modules

| Dependency | Notes |
|---|---|
| `public/kg_api.php` | KG tree, node detail, mini graph data |
| `generator_config` table | All LLM generation |
| `App\Oracle\Bloom` | Optional creative seeding — non-fatal if absent |
| SortableJS (CDN) | Drag-and-drop ingredient grid and pot |
| Sigma.js 2.4 + Graphology 0.25 (CDN) | Mini graph visualiser |
| `marked.js` (CDN) | Markdown rendering in node detail modal |
| `public/modal_frame_details.php` | Included at foot of `index.php` as fallback `showMiniGraphModal()` |
| `bootstrap.php` / `env_locals.php` | PDO connection, session, `$spw` platform object |

**Modules that link into Scene Kitchen from the dashboard:** The main SAGE dashboard and navigation link to `/sceki/` (v2). The legacy `/scene_kitchen.php` path still exists but uses the older OOP-based v1 architecture.

**Downstream modules that consume Scene Kitchen output:**
- Enhanimaticism (frame generation queue picks up `sketches` records)
- VidBat (sketch-linked frames)
- PLUSH Editor (sketch IDs referenced in beat blocks)
- Showrunner / Auto-Narrative Laboratory (sketch description as narrative input)

---

### Known State / Notes

- **Two parallel implementations exist:** `public/sceki/` (v2, PDO-only, active) and the combination of `public/scene_kitchen.php` + `public/api/kitchen_ajax.php` + `src/SceneKitchen/` (v1, OOP/Doctrine). The v1 codebase uses `KitchenChef`, `AbstractIngredient`, and the four `*Ingredient` classes under `src/SceneKitchen/Ingredients/`. The v2 inlines all hydration logic into `api.php` helper functions and uses `KitchenChefV2` in `public/sceki/KitchenChef.php`. Both implementations write to the same `sketches`, `sketch_ingredients`, and `meta_sketches` tables.

- **`is_ingredient` flag:** All entity tables gate ingredient visibility on `is_ingredient=1`. If an entity does not appear in the ingredient grid, this flag should be checked first.

- **`description_raw` column:** v2''s `KitchenChefV2::saveSketch()` saves the original AI-generated description to both `description` and `description_raw`, so continuity rewrites applied later do not overwrite the original prompt. The v1 `KitchenChef::saveSketch()` only writes to `description`. `[VERIFY]` whether v1 was ever updated to mirror this behaviour.

- **Oracle Bloom integration:** The `App\Oracle\Bloom` class is wrapped in a try/catch in the cook action and is non-fatal. `[VERIFY]` current availability status of this class in the codebase.

- **Legacy `auto_recipe` action:** The v1 endpoint uses `action=auto_recipe`; the v2 uses `action=random_recipe`. The v1 `scene_kitchen.php` frontend calls `/api/kitchen_ajax.php` with the `auto_recipe` action.

- **`anivoc_categories` table:** The random recipe action queries `anivoc_categories.table_name` to pick a random Anivoc ingredient category. This table is referenced but not included in the provided schema dump. `[VERIFY]` schema.

- **KG Subpot `id` encoding:** The `_kg_subpot` ingredient type encodes selected node IDs as a `_`-separated string in the `id` field (e.g. `kg_1_4_17`). `buildKgSubpotText()` parses these back to integers via `array_values(array_filter(explode(''_'', ...), ''is_numeric''))`.

- **`fetch_visuals` action in `kg_api.php`:** This action is present in `kg_api.php` and references `sketch_lore_history`, `sketch_analysis`, and `ag_nodes` tables — none of which appear in the Scene Kitchen source dump. It is part of the KG view module, not Scene Kitchen itself, and appears in `kg_api.php` for co-location convenience. `[VERIFY]` whether `ag_nodes` and `sketch_lore_history` are documented separately.

- **v1 `fetchAvailable()` filter difference:** `SketchTemplateIngredient::fetchAvailable()` in v1 does not filter on `is_ingredient=1` (only `active=1 AND entity_type=''sketches''`), while the v2 `api.php` adds `AND is_ingredient=1`. This may produce different result sets between the two versions.
