# SAGE Module Documentation — Writers Room Forge (`wroom.php`)

*SAGE AI 2.0 Module Library — The Anima Chronicles*
*Generated for: SAGE 2.0 Alpha Release*

---

## 1. Introduction

The Writers Room Forge is SAGE''s AI-powered narrative architecture tool for *The Anima Chronicles* — a structured thinking environment designed not to generate scenes, but to analyse, stress-test, and develop the series'' 60-episode story architecture. It provides a persistent, conversational workspace where the showrunner can interrogate narrative threads, map consequences of structural decisions, audit dramatic tension across seasons, and test story coherence against a constitutional framework built around the central thematic axis of Partnership versus Force. The module is tightly coupled with the SAGE Knowledge Graph system, from which lore context can be injected directly into any session, and with the Generator Forge, which supplies the AI configuration driving all responses via the `wroom_architect_v1` generator profile.

---

## 2. Module Details

### Purpose & Scope

The Writers Room Forge sits at the narrative architecture layer of the SAGE pipeline — between the raw lore and world-building stored in the Knowledge Graph and the production-facing beat assembly work done in PLUSH. It is the primary workspace for structural decisions: thread management, consequence mapping, coherence testing, and systemic auditing.

**Inputs:**
- Showrunner text queries (natural language prompts)
- Story phase and session context (phase, current status, focus question, registry version)
- The Thread Registry (all narrative threads, typed and statused)
- Session Delta history (decisions and deferred items from prior sessions)
- Injected KG node content (lore, edges, character/location excerpts)

**Outputs:**
- AI architectural analysis responses in the chat viewport
- Session Deltas (decisions made, threads touched, registry update notes)
- Thread Registry entries (created or updated)
- Chekhov Debt records
- Exportable prompt text files (offline/Export Mode)

---

### Key Features

#### Six-Protocol Narrative Architecture System

Every query is routed through one of six analytical protocols, selectable from the input bar or applied automatically:

| Protocol | Name | Function |
|---|---|---|
| A | Trace Thread | Maps a thread''s full structural function, episode span, typed connections, open tensions, and Chekhov debts |
| B | Map Consequences | Projects a structural decision forward across immediate, medium, and long-range episode windows |
| C | Test Coherence | Evaluates whether two or more story elements are doing productive or redundant thematic work |
| D | Structural Options | Generates 2–3 alternative structural paths with consequence chains and Constitution-aligned reasoning |
| E | Tension Audit | Surveys all active/escalating/crisis threads for fatigue, crowding, or premature collapse risk |
| F | Stress-Test Decision | Full adversarial audit: 3 structural objections + all 10 Failure Mode checks + VERDICT (SURVIVES / SURVIVES_WITH_COSTS / FAILS) |

Protocols are selected via pill buttons in the input bar. AUTO mode lets the AI infer the appropriate protocol from the query. Quick-launch buttons in the welcome screen pre-select a protocol and focus the input field.

#### Thread Registry

A persistent, typed registry of all narrative threads. Each thread record holds:

- Thread ID (e.g. `T-001`), name, type (Cosmic / Civil / Character / Thematic / Revelation)
- Active seasons, lifecycle status (DORMANT through CLOSED)
- Thematic axis, tensions held open, open showrunner questions
- Chekhov debts (setups requiring payoff)
- Typed connection edges (using controlled vocabulary: REINFORCES, DEPENDS_ON, MIRRORS, FEEDS, etc.)

Threads can be selected (checked) from the left panel to be included as focused context in the next query. The AI automatically detects thread ID references (`T-###`) in its own responses and adds them to the current session delta''s thread list.

Thread management UI includes search, type filters (All / Cosmic / Civil / Char / Theme / Reveal), and an inline edit modal with full field editing. New threads surfaced by the AI in a session appear as draft-promoted entries in the Delta panel; they can be promoted to the full registry via the same modal.

#### Session Delta Tracking

Each working session accumulates a delta — a structured record of what was decided, deferred, and touched. The Session Delta panel (right flyout) captures:

- **Decisions Made** — tag-list input, added via Enter key
- **Decisions Deferred** — same pattern
- **Threads Touched / Proposed** — auto-populated from AI responses; draft threads shown in amber, registered threads in default style
- **Registry Updates Needed** — free-text field for notes on edits needed in the Thread Registry

Saving a delta commits it to the `wroom_deltas` table and clears the draft. Past deltas can be loaded back into the draft panel to resume a prior session''s context. Deltas are included in the AI system prompt (last 3 sessions), giving the AI structural memory of prior decisions.

#### KG Context Injection

A Knowledge Graph picker modal allows the showrunner to select nodes from the full KG tree (hierarchical folder/node view with checkbox selection) or via semantic search (natural language query against ChromaDB, returning ranked results by relevance score). Selected nodes can inject:

- **Lore content** — full node text
- **Edges** — typed relationship edges to neighbouring nodes

Injected content is written into the "Additional Context / Notes" field as a delimited block (`═══ KNOWLEDGE GRAPH CONTEXT ═══ … ═══ END KG CONTEXT ═══`), which is included in every subsequent query until changed. Re-injecting replaces the block in-place rather than appending.

The semantic search sub-tab auto-selects hits scoring above 0.35 and shows an excerpt + relevance score bar per result. Top-N count is configurable (10 / 20 / 35 / 50).

#### Auto-Draft Mode

A checkbox in the input bar appends an execution override instruction to any query, directing the AI to resolve its own open questions with the most dramatically compelling canon-compliant choices and output a polished 3–5 sentence "FINAL BEAT" narrative description — ready for injection into the master outline. This is a prompt-engineering augmentation; it does not alter the underlying protocol system.

#### Offline / Export Mode

A mode toggle in the input bar switches the module from live API mode to Export Mode. In this mode, submitting a query serialises the full prompt (system message + conversation history) to a downloadable `.txt` file rather than calling the API. The showrunner can then paste an AI response manually via the "Inject Response" robot button. This allows use with external AI interfaces (e.g. Claude.ai directly) when the local API pipeline is unavailable.

#### Context Deduplication

The module implements a snapshot-deduplication system for multi-turn conversations. Before storing each user message, it compares the current context fields (phase, status, focus, extra, selected threads) to the most recent stored snapshot using a stable JSON serialisation. If context is unchanged, it stores a lightweight reference (`{ ref: N }`) pointing to the prior snapshot index rather than duplicating the full context block. When building API messages, these references are rendered as compact `[CONTEXT: unchanged from step N]` notes, reducing token consumption across long sessions.

#### Chekhov Debt Tracker

A dedicated panel (right flyout, Chekhov tab) tracks setups that must pay off. Entries are linked to thread IDs, carry a deadline episode field, and toggle between UNPAID and PAID states. Chekhov debts declared in thread records are automatically surfaced as tracker entries on save.

#### Failure Mode Checklist

A static checklist of the 10 defined failure modes for the series architecture, displayed in the right flyout (Failures tab). These modes are also embedded in the AI system prompt as part of Protocol F execution. The checklist UI shows current status (unchecked / flagged / clear) per mode, though real-time status updating from AI responses is not yet automated — the panel serves as a manual reference and annotation surface. `[VERIFY]`

#### Multi-Session Chat History

Each conversation is stored as a named session with a UUID. The Chats tab in the left flyout lists all past sessions in reverse chronological order. Sessions can be loaded (re-rendering the full conversation) or permanently deleted. The most recent session is auto-loaded on page load.

---

### Data Model

| Table | Role |
|---|---|
| `wroom_settings` | One row per user; persists all context fields, session settings, KG selection state, offline mode flag, and current draft delta as JSON. Primary key: `user_id`. |
| `wroom_threads` | Thread registry. One row per thread per user. Stores all thread fields including `is_selected` for focus state. Fully replaced on each save (delete-then-insert). |
| `wroom_conversation` | Conversation turns. Each row is one message (user or assistant), linked to a `session_id` UUID. Stores role, content, protocol, timestamp, and `context_snapshot` as JSON (full snapshot or `{ ref: N }` reference). |
| `wroom_chat_sessions` | Session metadata index. Stores `session_id`, `user_id`, title (derived from first query), and `updated_at`. Used to render the Chats tab list. |
| `wroom_deltas` | Saved session deltas. Each row holds decisions, deferred items, threads (as JSON array of `{id, name, line}` objects), and free-text update notes. Stored in insert order; loaded in DESC order. Fully replaced on each save. |
| `wroom_chekhov` | Chekhov debt records. Per-user, per-thread. Fields: `thread_id`, `description`, `ep` (deadline episode), `is_paid`. Fully replaced on each save. |
| `generator_config` | AI configuration table (shared across SAGE). The `wroom_architect_v1` config (id 125) supplies the system role, protocol instructions, and model selection for all Writers Room sessions. |

**ChromaDB:** The semantic search sub-tab in the KG picker calls `/kg_api.php` with action `semantic_query`, which queries the ChromaDB vector store. The Writers Room itself does not interact with ChromaDB directly — it is mediated via the KG API.

---

### API / Backend Integration

#### `/wroom_api.php` — Primary Backend

| Action (GET/POST) | Method | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `load_state` | GET | Loads full user state: settings, context, threads, chekhov, deltas, chat sessions, and most recent conversation |
| `save_state` | POST | Persists all state atomically within a transaction: settings, threads, chekhov, deltas, chat session metadata, and conversation turns |
| `load_chat` | GET (`?session_id=`) | Returns full conversation for a given session UUID |
| `delete_chat` | POST | Removes a chat session and all its conversation rows |
| `generate` | POST | Constructs the full prompt from Generator Forge config + Thread Registry + Delta history, then calls the SAGE AI provider and returns the raw response |
| `export_prompt` | POST | Same as `generate` but returns the assembled message array as JSON for download rather than calling the API |

The `generate` action uses `GeneratorRepository` to look up the active `wroom_architect_v1` config. The system message is built dynamically from: the stored system role → protocol instructions → the full Thread Registry (JSON) → recent session deltas (JSON) → a depth instruction derived from the session depth setting (brief / standard / deep).

The AI call is delegated to `$spw->getAIProvider()` — the central SAGE AI orchestration layer. Model and generation parameters (`temperature`, `max_tokens`) are drawn from the generator config''s `parameters` field. Default `max_tokens` is 2500 if not specified in config.

#### `/kg_api.php` — Knowledge Graph API

Called directly from the frontend for KG picker operations:

| Action | Description |
|---|---|
| `fetch_tree` | Returns full KG node tree (folders + nodes) for the picker |
| `semantic_query` | Queries ChromaDB with a natural language string, returns ranked hits with name, type, category, excerpt, content status, and relevance score |
| `focused_snapshot` | Given an array of node DB IDs, returns a structured snapshot of lore content and/or edges for injection into context |

---

### UI & Interaction

**Layout:** Full-viewport single-column layout (`wr-layout`). The conversation viewport occupies the full width. Both sidebars are flyout panels triggered by hamburger buttons in the header — left flyout for Context & Registry, right flyout for Session Tracking. A shared backdrop overlay closes both flyouts on tap.

**Header:** Logo, phase indicator (session phase + topic label, appears after first message), New Session button, and the right hamburger. A theme toggle button is present in the markup but hidden by default (`display:none`) — `[VERIFY]` whether this is intentionally suppressed or a CSS oversight.

**Left Flyout — four tabs:**
- *Context* — Story phase selector, current status textarea, focus question, registry version, additional context/notes (with KG picker trigger button)
- *Threads* — Searchable, filterable thread list with inline selection and edit buttons; Add Thread button
- *Deltas* — History of saved session deltas, clickable to reload
- *Chats* — Chat session list with load/delete actions

**Right Flyout — three tabs:**
- *Delta* — Live draft delta editor (decisions, deferred, threads auto-populated, registry notes, Save Delta button)
- *Failures* — Static failure mode checklist
- *Chekhov* — Debt tracker with toggle-to-paid interaction and add button

**Input Bar:** Protocol selector pills + Auto-Draft checkbox + mode toggle button, then textarea + send button. Textarea auto-resizes up to 200px. Enter sends (Shift+Enter inserts newline). The Robot inject button appears only in Export Mode.

**Message Rendering:** User messages appear right-aligned with amber bubble. AI messages appear left-aligned with a dark card bubble. AI response text is rendered with lightweight markdown parsing: `## headings` become amber section labels, `**bold**` becomes highlighted text, bullet/dash lines become left-bordered tension blocks, `T-###` IDs become clickable thread reference chips (opening the thread modal), and `VERDICT: SURVIVES/FAILS/SURVIVES_WITH_COSTS` is rendered as a colour-coded badge.

**KG Picker Modal:** Two-tab modal (Graph Tree / Semantic Slice). Tree tab renders the full KG hierarchy with collapsible folders, tri-state checkboxes (checked / indeterminate / unchecked), and persistent open/closed folder state stored in `localStorage`. Semantic tab provides a query input + top-N select + Search button, renders ranked results with relevance bars and type/status indicators, and supports toggle-all selection.

**Modals:** Thread editor modal (grid layout, full field set), Session Settings modal (depth, auto-failure, session topic). All modals close on backdrop click or Escape key.

**Toasts:** Bottom-right toast stack with success (green border), error (red border), info (amber border) variants. Auto-dismiss at configurable duration (default 2800ms).

**Mobile:** Fully responsive and mobile-first. Flyout panels constrained to `min(300px, 88vw)`. All interactive targets are touch-sized. Viewport uses `100dvh` for iOS safe-area compatibility. Scrollbars are styled to 4px width.

---

### Dependencies & Related Modules

| Dependency | Nature |
|---|---|
| **Generator Forge** (`generator_forge.php`) | Supplies the `wroom_architect_v1` AI configuration record. Model, system role, and protocol instructions are all managed there, not in Writers Room itself. |
| **Knowledge Graph** (`kg_view.php` / `kg_api.php`) | KG tree data and semantic search are fetched via `kg_api.php`. The KG picker UI mirrors patterns from the KG view. |
| **PLUSH Editor** | Downstream consumer of Writers Room output — beat decisions made here are eventually formalised into PLUSH highlight blocks. No direct code integration. |
| **SAGE AI Provider** | Central AI orchestration (`$spw->getAIProvider()`) handles model routing and API calls. |
| **Bootstrap Icons 1.11.3** | Icon library (CDN). |
| **Google Fonts** | Space Mono + Syne, loaded via CDN. |

No direct dependencies on: VidBat, DAW, Showrunner, Fuzz Forge, or Content Hub.

